INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`material`) VALUES
('\n<div>\n<p>\nThe internet has come a long way, from static web pages to social media and smart apps. Now, we are entering a new era called Web3, and it is changing the internet as we know it.\n</p>\n<br>\n\n<p >\nBut what exactly is Web3?\nWeb3 (short for Web 3.0) is the next generation of the internet that aims to decentralize control from big tech companies and give more power, ownership, and privacy back to users.\n</p>\n<br>\n\n<p>\nHistorically, interactions between two different users on the internet relied on big tech companies like Google, Facebook, or Amazon to provide the platforms for transmitting information. Because these tech companies have access to the identities and activities of users, they also control the information being transmitted, resulting in a lack of true privacy.\n</p>\n<br>\n\n<p>\nSimply put, Web3 is the decentralized version of the internet built using cryptography, blockchain technology, and decentralized protocols. It is designed to give more control to users by allowing everyday internet users to interact safely on the internet without a third centralized party controlling their activities. Users of Web3 can own their data, manage digital assets like cryptocurrencies, and interact online without needing to trust or depend on central authorities.\n</p>\n</div>\n\n\n<br>    \n <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> BIG AND TECHNICAL WORDS?</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n     <p> \n     We\'re sure \"blockchain\", \"cryptography\", and \"decentralized protocols\" sound even more confusing than \"Web3\", but that\'s exactly why you\'re here. Stick around, and it will all make sense.\n</p> </div>\n<br><br>\n\n<p>\n <h2>A Quick History</h2> \nTo better understand Web3, it helps to look at what came before it:\n<p>\n<ul>\n    <li> <b>  Web1 (1990s–early 2000s) </b> : Commonly called the \"read-only\" internet, users could visit websites but could not interact with content.\n</li>\n    <li>  <b> Web2 (2000s–now) </b> : The \"read-and-write\" internet. This marks the rise of social media, cloud apps, and e-commerce. However, it also meant companies started collecting and controlling large amounts of user data.\n</li>\n    <li>  <b> Web3 </b> : The \"read-write-own\" internet. This version of the internet is about user control, decentralization, and digital ownership.\n</li>\n</ul>\n</p>\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n\n <h2>Key Features of Web3</h2>\n<p>\n<ol class=\"pl-3 space-y-2 list-decimal \">\n    <li>\n        <b>Decentralization</b>:\n        This means no single company or entity controls the entire network. Instead, it operates through many independent nodes (computers) distributed around the world.\n    </li>\n    \n\n    <li>\n        <b>Decentralized Applications (dApps):</b> Web3 apps run on peer-to-peer networks like blockchains, not on centralized servers. This means no single company owns or controls the apps or user data.\n\n    </li>\n\n    <li>\n     <b>Digital Ownership:</b> In Web3, you can own digital items—such as art, music, or game items—through tools like NFTs (Non-Fungible Tokens). These are stored in digital wallets that only the owner controls.\n    </li>\n\n\n    <li>\n        <b>Built-in Money System:</b> Web3 uses cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum to send money instantly without banks, middlemen, or borders.\n         This is the dominant aspect of Web3 and has generated significant interest among technology investors and crypto enthusiasts.\n    </li>\n\n    <li>\n        <b>Smart Contracts:</b>\n        These are self-executing programs on the blockchain that run automatically when specified conditions are met. For example, a smart contract can release payment only when a job is completed, without any human intervention.\n    </li>\n\n    <li>\n        <b>Open Source Code:</b>\n        Most Web3 projects are open source, meaning anyone can view, use, or improve the code. This encourages collaboration and community-driven innovation.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <b>Interoperability:</b>\n        Web3 apps can seamlessly work together. For example, you can use your crypto wallet to buy an NFT on one platform and then use it in a game on another platform.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <b>Permissionless:</b>\n        Anyone can join and use Web3 without needing permission from a central authority. You don’t need to create an account or get approved by a company.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <b>Transparency:</b>All transactions and data on the blockchain are visible to everyone. This means you can verify what’s happening without needing to trust a company.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <b>Community Governance:</b>Many Web3 projects are governed by their users through decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs). This means decisions are made collectively, not by a single company.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n        <b>Privacy and Identity:</b>Web3 uses your crypto wallet as your identity. You control what information to share, and there are no passwords to remember.\n    </li>\n\n</ol>\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n \n <h2> Real-Life Examples </h2>\n\n <p>\n<ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] space-y-4 list-inside \" >\n    <li>\n        Crypto wallets like MetaMask let you buy, store, and use cryptocurrencies or NFTs.\n    </li>\n    <li>Decentralized apps like Uniswap let you swap tokens without a bank or exchange.\n</li>\n    <li>NFT marketplaces like OpenSea let you create, buy, or sell digital art that you truly own.\n</li>\n    <li> Innovations like Filecoin, Arweave, or Storj use blockchain technology to create a decentralized cloud storage network.\n</li>\n<li>The use of smart contracts for automated software licensing.</li>\n<li>Creation and operation of decentralised identity systems using crypto.</li>\n</ol>\n</p>\n<p>These use cases and many more highlight the beauty of this rapidly evolving innovation.</p>\n<br><br>\n\n    \n    <h2> Why Should You Care? </h2>\n<p class=\"pl-3\">\n    \n\n          Technology is constantly evolving, so everyone must keep learning to stay ahead.\n          Web3 protects your privacy and identity while giving you ownership of your digital life.\n          <br><br>\n          It offers financial freedom through crypto tools and strategic investments, opening opportunities to earn, build, and participate in global communities regardless of location.\n          <br><br>\n          It solves the international payments problem, allowing anyone to easily pay for and access services globally from anywhere.\n    \n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n <h2>Challenges in Learning Web3</h2> \n<p>\nSome challenges you might face while learning Web3 include: \n    <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside space-y-3\">\n    <li>It can be confusing at first (wallets, gas fees, keys, etc.)….This is exactly why we are here.\n</li>\n    <li>Some DApps have steep learning curves and require significant experience to master.\n</li>\n    <li>Scams and mistakes can be costly since blockchain transactions are irreversible.\n</li>\n    <li>Governments are still developing regulations for the Web3 space.\n</li>\n<li>\n  Information overload due to the complex and technical nature of blockchain principles.\n</li>\n</ol>\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n<p> \n   But just like the early days of the internet, Web3 is growing fast, and people who learn early will benefit while helping shape the future; If you\'re curious and ready to explore, Welcome once again.\n</p>\n\n\n\n'),
('<p class=\"pl-3\"> \n  <p>Blockchain technology is one of the most revolutionary innovations of the 21st century, powering digital currencies like Bitcoin and transforming industries with its promise of transparency, security, and decentralization. But what exactly is blockchain?</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>At its core, a <strong>blockchain</strong> is a distributed digital ledger that stores information in a secure and tamper-proof way.</p>\n  <br>\n  \n  <p>\n   Essentially, a blockchain is a network of computers (nodes) linked together to store data in a tamper-proof manner. Unlike traditional databases controlled by a single entity (like a bank or company), a blockchain is <em>decentralized</em>, meaning it\'s shared across many computers or nodes. Each entry in this ledger is called a <strong>block</strong>, and these blocks are linked or \"chained\" together in chronological order, which is why it\'s called a blockchain.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl\">How a blockchain works</h2>\n\n  <ol class=\"space-y-2 list-dash list-inside \">\n    <li><b>Transaction Occurs:</b> A user initiates a transaction, such as sending cryptocurrency or recording data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transaction is Verified:</strong> A network of computers (called nodes) validates the transaction using algorithms.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transaction is Added to a Block:</strong> Once verified, the transaction is grouped with others into a block.</li>\n    <li><strong>Block is Added to the Chain:</strong> The block is attached to the existing blockchain in a permanent, unchangeable way.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <p class=\"pl-3\">Once a block is added, the data it contains is nearly impossible to alter without changing every subsequent block—a feature that makes blockchain highly secure.</p>\n\n\n  <br>\n    \n<div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> ANALOGY: HOW BLOCKCHAIN WORKS </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n  <p>Imagine a classroom where every student has a notebook. This notebook is used to record every time someone borrows or returns a book from the class library.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h3>These Distinct Steps Follow:</h3>\n\n  <ol class=\"pl-5 indent-5\">\n    <li><strong>A Transaction Happens:</strong> John borrows a book titled \"Science Today\".</li>\n    <li><strong>Everyone Sees It:</strong> Instead of one person writing it down, all students copy the same transaction into their notebooks: <br>\n      <em>\"John borrowed \'Science Today\' at 10:00 AM\"</em>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Information is Locked In:</strong> Once all students write it down, that page in the notebook is considered complete and can\'t be changed.</li>\n    <li><strong>The Chain Continues:</strong> The next transaction (e.g., Mary returns \"Math Basics\") is recorded on a new page, following the previous one.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <p class=\"pl-3\">This way, the class keeps a tamper-proof, shared history of every library transaction. If someone tries to cheat and change their notebook, it won’t match others—and everyone will know!</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h3> How This Relates to Blockchain:</h3>\n\n  <ol class=\"pl-5 indent-5\">\n    <li><strong>The notebook</strong> represents the blockchain.</li>\n    <li><strong>The students</strong> are like the network nodes (computers).</li>\n    <li><strong>The recorded entries</strong> are the blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>The linking of pages</strong> is the chain of blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consensus among students</strong> ensures no one can fake or alter history.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n  <p><strong>Summary:</strong> Just like the classroom notebook system, blockchain creates a shared, secure, and permanent record of transactions—open to all, but impossible to alter without agreement from everyone involved.</p>\n\n</div>\n\n\n\n<br>\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl \">Key features of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <ol class=\"list-decimal list-inside space-y-3 \">\n    <li><strong>Decentralization:</strong> No single authority controls the blockchain. All participants have access to the same information.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transparency:</strong> Transactions are visible to all participants in the network.</li>\n    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Blockchain uses cryptographic algorithms to ensure data is secure and cannot be tampered with.</li>\n    <li><strong>Immutability:</strong> Once data is added to the blockchain, it cannot be changed or deleted.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consensus Mechanism:</strong> Decisions are made collectively by the network, usually through methods like Proof of Work (PoW) or Proof of Stake (PoS).</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl \">Applications of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <p class=\"pl-3 \">Blockchain extends far beyond cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin or Ethereum. It has diverse applications across multiple sectors:</p>\n\n  <ol class=\"list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-3\">\n    <li><strong>Finance:</strong> Enabling peer-to-peer payments and cryptocurrency transactions, eliminating intermediaries, and increasing settlement speed.</li>\n    <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Storing patient records securely and giving patients control over their data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Supply Chain:</strong> Tracking products from source to destination, ensuring authenticity and quality.</li>\n    <li><strong>Voting Systems:</strong> Creating tamper-proof digital voting systems to improve transparency and trust.</li>\n    <li><strong>Real Estate:</strong> Recording property ownership and transaction history in a secure manner.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl \">Advantages of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <ol class=\"list-inside list-decimal space-y-3 \">\n    <li>Reduces fraud and corruption through immutability and transparency</li>\n    <li>Improves efficiency and speed of transactions with 24/7 operation</li>\n    <li>Lowers operational costs by eliminating intermediaries and third-party fees</li>\n    <li>Empowers users with complete control over their own data and assets</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl \">Challenges of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <p class=\"pl-3\">\n  <ol class=\"list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-3\">\n    <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Some blockchains process transactions slowly and struggle with high transaction volumes.</li>\n    <li><strong>Energy Consumption:</strong> Proof of Work (PoW) consensus mechanisms consume significant amounts of electricity.</li>\n    <li><strong>Regulatory Uncertainty:</strong> Governments worldwide are still developing frameworks to regulate blockchain and crypto technologies.</li>\n    <li><strong>Complexity:</strong> The technology is complex and requires significant learning effort to fully understand and implement.</li>\n  </ol>\n  </p>\n  <br><br>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  <h2 class=\"font-bold text-2xl\">Conclusion</h2>\n\n  <p>Blockchain technology has the potential to transform industries by making systems more secure, transparent, and decentralized. While it comes with its own set of challenges, its advantages are far-reaching. As innovation continues, blockchain is likely to become an even more significant part of our digital future.</p>\n\n  <p><em>Understanding blockchain today means being ready for tomorrow’s world of technology and finance.</em></p>\n\n\n'),
('\n  <p>In the digital age, cryptography and cryptocurrency are becoming increasingly important, especially as the world moves toward decentralized systems, blockchain-based platforms, and digital finance. While they are often mentioned together, they are not the same thing. However, they are <em>deeply connected</em>.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2>What is Cryptography?</h2>\n  <p>Cryptography is the science of protecting data through mathematical techniques. Its goal is to secure communication and ensure that only intended recipients can understand the message or access the data.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2>Core Functions of Cryptography</h2>\n  <p>\n    Cryptography serves four main functions crucial for secure communication and data integrity:\n    </p>\n\n  <ol class=\"pl-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-2 \">\n    <li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> Prevents unauthorized access to information.</li>\n    <li><strong>Integrity:</strong> Ensures that information has not been altered.</li>\n    <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Verifies the identity of users or sources.</li>\n    <li><strong>Non-repudiation:</strong> Prevents denial of involvement in a transaction.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n    <br>\n  <h2>Types of Cryptography</h2>\n  <ol class=\"pl-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman]\">\n    <li><strong>Symmetric Encryption:</strong> Uses the same key to encrypt and decrypt data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Asymmetric Encryption:</strong> Uses a public and private key pair.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n  <p>\n    Symmetric encryption is faster and suitable for encrypting large amounts of data, while asymmetric encryption is more secure and is used for key exchange and digital signatures. Both types of cryptography are essential for cryptocurrencies, providing the necessary security and trust mechanisms.\n    <br>\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n    <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> NOTEWORTHY</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>Cryptography is essential in Web3 and blockchain studies. However, deeper knowledge of cryptography should be sourced through dedicated academic texts and research, which are beyond the scope of this lesson.</p>\n    </div>\n\n\n\n\n\n  <br><br>\n  <h2>What is Cryptocurrency?</h2>\n  <p>Cryptocurrency is a type of digital or virtual currency that uses cryptography to secure transactions, control the creation of new units, and validate asset transfers. At its core, it is a reward system for nodes participating in a blockchain.</p>\n<br><br>\n\n  <h2>Relationship Between Cryptography and Cryptocurrency</h2>\n  <p>Cryptography makes cryptocurrency possible. Without cryptography, cryptocurrencies would be easy to counterfeit, vulnerable to fraud, and impossible to verify. Therefore, cryptography provides the foundation for the security, integrity, and trustworthiness of cryptocurrencies.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    Cryptography enables cryptocurrencies through several key concepts and technologies. Here\'s how they work together and the benefits cryptography provides:\n</p>\n<br>\n<div class=\"pl-3\">\n  <h3>1. Digital Signatures</h3>\n  <p class=\"pl-2\">When someone sends cryptocurrency, they must prove ownership of the funds using a <strong>private key</strong>.\n  <ul class=\"indent-2 list-inside\">\n    <li>A <strong>digital signature</strong> is created using cryptographic algorithms and verified by others using the sender\'s <strong>public key</strong>.</li>\n    <li>\n      This ensures authenticity without revealing the private key. It\'s like signing a check, but mathematically and in a way that cannot be forged.\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n\n\n  <h3>2. Hash Functions</h3>\n  <p>A hash function converts input into a fixed-length string. It is one-way and impossible to reverse; even small changes in input create vastly different outputs.</p>\n  <ol class=\"indent-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman]\">\n    <li><b>Use cases:</b></li>\n    <li>Generation of transaction IDs</li>\n    <li>Block verification</li>\n    <li>Proof-of-Work (e.g., mining)</li>\n  </ol>\n   <p>These special functions are only possible through cryptography.</p>\n\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h3>3. Wallets and Key Pairs</h3>\n  <p>A crypto wallet stores your keys, not your money.</p>\n  <ol class=\"indent-3 list-inside\">\n    <li><strong>Public Key:</strong> Like a bank account number that you can share publicly.</li>\n    <li><strong>Private Key:</strong> Like your ATM PIN—never share this with anyone.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <p>These special keys are generated using cryptographic algorithms, ensuring that only the owner can access their funds.</p>\n\n  <br>\n  <h3>4. Secure Transactions on the Blockchain</h3>\n  <p>Each cryptocurrency transaction is encrypted, signed, and verified using cryptographic functions. The blockchain network itself serves as the trust layer—no banks needed.</p>\n  <br>\n\n\n\n  <h3>5. Consensus Mechanisms</h3>\n  <p>Cryptocurrencies use consensus mechanisms to agree on and validate transactions:</p>\n  <ol class=\"indent-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman]\">\n    <li><strong>Proof of Work (PoW):</strong> Mining using computational puzzles.</li>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Stake (PoS):</strong> Validators hold coins to propose and validate blocks.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n</div>\n\n\n  <h2>Example Applications</h2>\n  <ol class=\"indent-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-2\">\n    <li><strong>Bitcoin & Ethereum:</strong> Core cryptographic blockchain networks.</li>\n    <li><strong>NFTs:</strong> Verified using cryptographic proofs.</li>\n    <li><strong>zk-SNARKs:</strong> Enables private, verified transactions.</li>\n    <li><strong>Signal & Secure Messaging:</strong> Uses cryptographic protocols for privacy.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2>Challenges of Cryptocurrency</h2>\n  <ol class=\"indent-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-2\">\n    <li><strong>Key Loss:</strong> Losing your private keys means losing access to your funds permanently, with no way to recover them.</li>\n    <li><strong>User Error:</strong> Decentralization means there\'s no central authority to recover lost or misplaced funds.</li>\n    <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Some blockchains process transactions slowly and require enormous resources to scale effectively.</li>\n    <li><strong>Quantum Threat:</strong> Advances in quantum computing could potentially break current encryption. This is an anticipated long-term security concern.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <br>\n\n  <h2>Summary</h2>\n  <p>Cryptography and cryptocurrency are inseparable. One is the science of security, and the other is the practical application of that science to digital money. Together, they enable a new era of digital finance where individuals have complete control over their assets.</p>\n\n'),
('\n    <p>\n      <b>\n        <i>\n      \n        Remember our classroom analogy for blockchain? Let\'s continue with it.\n      </i>\n      </b>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n<div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> ANALOGY CONT\'D: HOW BLOCKCHAIN WORKS </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n  <p>Imagine a classroom where every student has a notebook. This notebook is used to record every time someone borrows or returns a book from the class library.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h3>These Distinct Steps Follow:</h3>\n\n  <ol class=\"pl-5 indent-5\">\n    <li><strong>A Transaction Happens:</strong> John borrows a book titled \"Science Today\".</li>\n    <li><strong>Everyone Sees It:</strong> Instead of one person writing it down, all students copy the same transaction into their notebooks: <br>\n      <em>\"John borrowed \'Science Today\' at 10:00 AM\"</em>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Information is Locked In:</strong> Once all students write it down, that page in the notebook is considered complete and can\'t be changed.</li>\n    <li><strong>The Chain Continues:</strong> The next transaction (e.g., Mary returns \"Math Basics\") is recorded on a new page, following the previous one.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <p class=\"pl-3\">This way, the class keeps a tamper-proof, shared history of every library transaction. If someone tries to cheat and change their notebook, it won’t match others—and everyone will know!</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h3> How This Relates to Blockchain:</h3>\n\n  <ol class=\"pl-5 indent-5\">\n    <li><strong>The notebook</strong> represents the blockchain.</li>\n    <li><strong>The students</strong> are like the network nodes (computers).</li>\n    <li><strong>The recorded entries</strong> are the blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>The linking of pages</strong> is the chain of blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consensus among students</strong> ensures no one can fake or alter history.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n    <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> WHERE CRYPTOCURRENCY COMES IN</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n    <p>\n        Writing transactions into the notebook takes time, effort, and honesty. To ensure students record accurately, the class introduces a reward system: they award <strong>\"ClassCoins\"</strong> each time a student correctly verifies and locks in a page.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p><strong>For instance:</strong> <br>  \n            When a student (like <strong>Alice</strong>) helps confirm and lock in a page of transactions, she earns <strong>ClassCoins</strong> as a reward. These coins have value in the classroom—perhaps Alice can use them to borrow extra books, trade with others, or gain special privileges. The total number of <strong>ClassCoins</strong> is limited, so they remain valuable.\n     </p>    \n     <br>   \n       \n\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">In this analogy, <strong>ClassCoins</strong> represent cryptocurrency. Just as students earn ClassCoins for helping maintain the notebook, blockchain network participants (called miners or validators) earn cryptocurrency (like Bitcoin or Ethereum) for helping verify and secure transactions. This reward system incentivizes honesty and participation, making the blockchain trustworthy and functional.</p>\n</div>\n<br><br>\n \n <h2>Why is Crypto Accepted as Money?</h2> \n\n   <p>\n    In our analogy, ClassCoins derive value from their utility and scarcity. The value of ClassCoins is determined by what people are willing to pay for them. Similarly, cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum came to be accepted as money through the same mechanism: their value is established by market demand and utility.\n    <br>\n   </p>\n    <br>\n  <p>Ultimately, money is based on shared belief. If many people believe that a particular material with certain properties serves as a medium of exchange, then that material becomes \"money.\"</p>\n  <p>Cryptocurrency (like Bitcoin or Ethereum) is accepted as money because it possesses the essential properties of money, even though it\'s digital and decentralized. <br><br>To be accepted as money, an item must have these key properties and functions:</p>\n<br><br>\n\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>1. Medium of exchange</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\"> People must be able to use it to buy goods and services.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>2. Store of Value </b>  </td>\n    <td>It must keep its value over time so people can save it.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>3. Unit of Account</b>  </td>\n    <td>Prices must be expressed in it.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>4. Divisibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be easily divided into smaller parts.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>5. Portability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be easy to carry and transfer.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>6. Durability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must withstand wear and tear.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>7. Fungibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">Each unit must be interchangeable (just as a one dollar bill is the same as another).</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>10. Acceptability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">People must generally agree to accept it as payment.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>11. Limited Supply</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">There should be controlled supply to prevent inflation.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>12. Security</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be secure against counterfeiting.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>13. Accessibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It should be easy for people to access and use.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>\n\n<br>\n\n  <p>These functions are why we accept things like gold, silver, or even paper money as \"money\", because they allow us to trade, save, and measure value. Cryptocurrency meets these functions in many ways, and is largely accepted because:</p>\n<br>\n  <ol class=\"space-y-4 list-decimal list-inside\"> \n\n      <li>\n      <strong>People Trust Its Technology:</strong>\n\n      Crypto is secured by blockchain technology and cryptography, making it tamper-proof, transparent, and decentralized. The world accepts it because the rules are clear, secure, and enforced by code rather than by banks or governments.\n</li>\n\n  <li>\n\n      <strong>It is Borderless and Fast:</strong>\n\n      With cryptocurrency:\n\n      <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside indent-4\">\n        <li>People can send money to anyone, anywhere in the world.</li>\n        <li>Transactions are fast and often cost less than traditional methods.</li>\n        <li>You don\'t need a bank or government permission.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      This makes crypto especially useful for international trade, remittances, and online payments, particularly in countries with unstable currencies or limited banking infrastructure.\n\n  </li>\n\n\n  <li>     \n       <strong>Limited Supply:</strong>\n      Bitcoin, for example, has a maximum supply of 21 million coins. This scarcity makes it similar to gold, which people value for its ability to hold value over time.\n  </li>\n\n\n  <li>\n      <strong>People Control Their Money:</strong>\n\n      Cryptocurrency gives users ownership and control over their funds without needing banks or governments. This means:\n        \n      <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside indent-4\">\n        <li>No one can freeze your account.</li>\n        <li>No one can stop your transactions.</li>\n        <li>No inflation from central banks printing more currency.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      This financial freedom is very appealing to many people, especially in places with corrupt or unstable governments.\n</li>\n\n</ol>\n<br>\n\n  <h2>How Did People Come to Believe That Cryptocurrency Is Money?</h2>\n <br>\n  <p>People came to believe that cryptocurrency is money due to a combination of economic utility, technological advancement, and social consensus. Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies began fulfilling the roles traditional money played as people used them to buy goods, saved them as investments, and priced items in cryptocurrency. <br>\n\n     Users trusted cryptocurrencies because they are built on secure, transparent, and decentralized blockchain technology. This meant their investments were safe and straightforward. In regions with unstable banks or hyperinflation, crypto became a viable alternative.</p>\n    <p>\n      As more people and institutions began to buy, use, and accept crypto, a belief formed: <em>\"If others treat it like money, maybe I should too.\"</em> This social proof helped drive adoption, and today, for many, crypto is not just digital money—it is a strong movement and an important aspect of modern finance and technology.\n  </p>\n\n  <br>\n  \n\n  <h2>Some Popular Cryptocurrencies Include:</h2>\n  <ol class=\"pl-3 list-inside list-[lower-roman] space-y-2\">\n    <li>Bitcoin (BTC)</li>\n    <li>Ethereum (ETH)</li>\n    <li>Litecoin (LTC)</li>\n    <li>Solana (SOL)</li>\n  </ol>\n\n\n'),
('\n  <p>Cryptocurrency can seem like a foreign language when you\'re just starting out. From blockchains and wallets to gas fees and HODL, the crypto world is full of unique terms. Understanding them is essential for anyone looking to get involved with cryptocurrency, whether as a user, investor, developer, or enthusiast.</p>\n\n  <p>Let\'s look at some of the most common and important crypto terminologies, all explained in simple terms.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <b>1. Blockchain/Network</b> \n  <p>A blockchain is a distributed digital ledger that records all transactions across a network of computers. Each group of transactions forms a \"block,\" and these blocks are linked together in a chain. It is the foundational technology behind cryptocurrencies—every blockchain has its own native coin.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>2. Coin or Token</b>\n  <p>A coin or token is a digital form of money built on blockchain technology and designed to be decentralized. Examples include Bitcoin, Ethereum, and Solana. Technically, coins are native to their own blockchains, while tokens are built on existing blockchains.</p>\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> In practice, the terms \"token\" and \"coin\" are often used interchangeably.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>3. Wallet</b>\n  <p>A wallet is a software or hardware tool used to store, send, and receive cryptocurrencies. It is similar to a bank account and contains your public and private keys, as well as your wallet address—all generated from your seed phrase.</p>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside indent-4 pl-4\">\n    <li><strong>Hot Wallet:</strong> Connected to the internet, e.g., MetaMask, Trustwallet, Phantom, etc.</li>\n    <li><strong>Cold Wallet:</strong> Offline and more secure, e.g., hardware wallets like Ledger, which are specialized devices for crypto transactions.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <b>4. Seed Phrase / Recovery Phrase</b>\n  <p>A seed phrase is a 12 or 24-word phrase that grants access to your wallet\'s private key. Anyone with these words in the correct order can access the wallet\'s funds. Therefore, seed phrases must be protected and never shared with anyone. It is recommended that you write them down and store them safely. Losing your seed phrase means permanently losing access to your funds.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>5. Private Key / Public Key</b>\n  <p>Private and public keys are unique cryptographic keys used in blockchain transactions. They are generated from seed phrases and are uniquely bound to a specific seed phrase. They are essential for securing your wallet and authorizing transactions.</p>\n  <p><strong>Never share your private key with anyone.</strong> If someone has your private key, they have full control of your wallet and can access and transfer your cryptocurrency without your permission.</p>\n  <p>Simply put:</p>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside indent-4 pl-4\">\n    <li><strong>Public Key:</strong> Shared openly and used to generate your wallet address for receiving funds.</li>\n    <li><strong>Private Key:</strong> Kept secret and used to authorize transactions. Losing or exposing this key means permanently losing access to your funds.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> A public key is not the same as a wallet address. The public key is a longer string of characters used to generate your wallet address. Never transfer funds to a public key.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <b>6. Wallet Address</b>\n    <p>A wallet address is a unique string of characters used to send or receive cryptocurrency, similar to a bank account number.</p>\n      <p>It is derived from your public key and can be shared with others to receive funds. Always double-check the address before sending crypto, as blockchain transactions are irreversible. To prevent mistakes, always copy and paste addresses rather than typing them manually.</p>\n  <p><strong>Example:</strong> A Bitcoin address looks like this: <code><b>1A1zP1eP5QGefi2DMPTfTL5SLmv7DivfNa</b></code></p>\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> Always ensure you are using the correct address format for the specific cryptocurrency you are dealing with, as different coins have different address formats. You will develop this knowledge with experience.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>7. Gas Fee</b>\n  <p>A gas fee is a small payment required to perform a transaction or execute a smart contract on a blockchain. Gas fees compensate network validators for processing your transaction.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>8. Gas Limit</b>\n  <p>The gas limit is the maximum amount of gas you are willing to spend on a transaction. If the transaction requires more gas than your specified limit, the transaction will fail.</p>\n<br>\n\n<b>9. DApp (Decentralized Application)</b>\n  <p>A DApp is an application that runs on a decentralized network, typically powered by smart contracts. DApps are open-source, operate autonomously, and are not controlled by any single entity.</p>  \n  <br>\n\n  <b>10. Faucet</b>\n  <p>A faucet is a website or app that distributes small amounts of cryptocurrency for free, usually to help new users learn how to use wallets and conduct transactions. Faucets are often used to distribute testnet coins to developers and testers.</p>\n<br>\n\n <b>11. Testnet</b>\n  <p>A testnet is a separate blockchain environment used for testing purposes. It allows developers to experiment with new features without risking real money. Testnets use test coins that have no monetary value.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>12. Exchange</b>\n  <p>A cryptocurrency exchange is a platform where you can buy, sell, or trade cryptocurrencies. Exchanges are categorized as:</p>\n   <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside pl-4 indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Centralized Exchange (CEX):</strong> Operated by a company, requires registration, and holds user funds (e.g., Binance, Coinbase, Gate.io, MEXC).</li>\n    <li><strong>Decentralized Exchange (DEX):</strong> Peer-to-peer trading without intermediaries; users retain control of their funds (e.g., Jupiter, Uniswap, Pancakeswap).</li> \n    <li><strong>Hybrid Exchange:</strong> Combines features of both CEX and DEX, offering security and usability balance (e.g., Kado, dYdX).</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n<b>13. Altcoin</b>\n  <p>Any cryptocurrency other than Bitcoin is called an altcoin (alternative coin). Examples include Ethereum, Litecoin, and Solana.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>14. Whitepaper</b>\n  <p>A whitepaper is a detailed document that explains the purpose, technology, and roadmap of a cryptocurrency or blockchain project. Bitcoin\'s whitepaper was published by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>15. Token Symbol & Decimals</b>\n  <p>Every cryptocurrency has a ticker symbol used to identify the token. For example, Bitcoin\'s ticker is BTC, Ethereum is ETH, and Solana is SOL.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>16. Tokenomics</b>\n    <p>Tokenomics, short for \"Token Economics,\" refers to the economic model behind a token—how it is created, distributed, used, and maintained to establish and sustain its value.</p>\n<br>\n\n\n\n <b>17. Total Supply</b>\n <p>The maximum number of tokens that will ever be created.</p>\n <br>\n\n\n <b>18. Circulating Supply</b>\n <p>The total number of tokens currently in public circulation.</p>\n <br>\n\n <b>19. Initial Supply</b>\n <p>The total number of tokens released at launch.</p>\n <br>\n\n  <b>20. Market Cap</b>\n  <p>Market capitalization is calculated as the price of a coin multiplied by the total number of coins in circulation. It is used to measure the size and relative popularity of a cryptocurrency.</p>\n  <br>\n\n <b>21. Burning</b>\n <p>Burning is the permanent removal of tokens to reduce supply. It is done by sending tokens to an inaccessible address. Token burning creates scarcity, thereby increasing the potential value of the remaining tokens.</p>\n <br>\n\n  <b>22. Emission Rate</b>\n  <p>Emission rate describes the rate at which new tokens are created and introduced into circulation. It can be measured per block, per day, or per year. It is an important aspect of tokenomics, influencing supply and demand dynamics.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>23. Mining</b>\n  <p>Mining is the process of validating transactions and adding them to the blockchain. It is primarily used in Proof of Work systems like Bitcoin. Miners are rewarded with newly created cryptocurrency for their computational work.</p>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <b>24. Proof of Work (PoW) vs Proof of Stake (PoS)</b>\n  <ol class=\"pl-4 indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Proof of Work (PoW):</strong> A consensus mechanism where miners solve complex mathematical puzzles to validate transactions and secure the network. PoW requires significant computational power and energy consumption.</li>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Stake (PoS):</strong> A consensus mechanism where validators are chosen to create new blocks based on the number of coins they hold and are willing to \"stake\" as collateral. PoS is more energy-efficient than PoW.</li> \n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n  <b>25. Staking</b>\n  <p>Staking involves locking up cryptocurrency in a wallet to support blockchain network operations. It is used in Proof of Stake systems, and stakers are rewarded with additional coins for their participation.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>26. Volatility</b>\n  <p>Volatility refers to how much and how quickly the price of a cryptocurrency changes. Cryptocurrencies are known for being highly volatile, with prices sometimes changing dramatically in short periods.</p>\n<br>\n  \n  <b>27. FUD</b>\n  <p>FUD stands for Fear, Uncertainty, and Doubt. It describes situations where negative news or rumors negatively affect the price of a cryptocurrency, often causing panic selling.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>28. HODL</b>\n  <p>Originally a typo of \"hold,\" HODL means \"Hold On for Dear Life.\" It encourages cryptocurrency holders to retain their coins long-term despite market downturns and short-term price fluctuations.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>29. Pump and Dump</b>\n  <p>A pump and dump is a manipulative scheme where the price of a cryptocurrency is artificially inflated (pumped) and then quickly sold off (dumped) for profit. This scheme often affects small or low-volume coins.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>30. Bear Market / Bull Market</b>\n  <ol class=\"pl-4 indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Bull Market:</strong> Prices are rising, and market optimism is high.</li>\n    <li><strong>Bear Market:</strong> Prices are falling, and market pessimism dominates.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n  <b>31. NFT (Non-Fungible Token)</b>\n  <p>A Non-Fungible Token is a type of digital asset that represents ownership of unique items such as art, music, or game collectibles. NFTs are typically built on blockchains like Ethereum.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>32. Airdrops</b>\n  <p>An airdrop is a distribution method where users are rewarded with cryptocurrency tokens for holding a specific cryptocurrency or participating in a project. Airdrops are commonly used to promote new projects or reward loyal community members.</p>\n     <p>To receive an airdrop, you typically need to hold a certain amount of a specific cryptocurrency in your wallet at a designated time, or you may need to complete specific tasks such as following social media accounts, joining a community, or contributing to the project\'s development.</p>\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong> Always be cautious of airdrops, as some may be scams or phishing attempts. Legitimate airdrops will never ask for your private key or seed phrase.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <b>33. ICO / IDO</b>\n  <ol class=\"pl-4 indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>ICO:</strong> Initial Coin Offering—a fundraising method where a new cryptocurrency project sells tokens to early investors.</li>\n    <li><strong>IDO:</strong> Initial DEX Offering—a similar fundraising process launched on decentralized exchanges.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br><br>\n  <p>Cryptocurrency is a rapidly evolving space with its own unique language. These terminologies are far more than buzzwords—they form the foundation for understanding how crypto works. Whether you plan to trade, invest, build, or simply learn, familiarizing yourself with these terms will help you navigate the crypto ecosystem with confidence and understanding.</p>\n\n'),
(' <h2> Whitepaper</h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency, was introduced by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 through a whitepaper titled\n    <strong>\"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\"</strong> It outlined a decentralized network enabling direct\n    financial transactions between parties without relying on trusted intermediaries. By solving the double-spending problem\n    through a consensus mechanism called <em>Proof of Work</em>, the whitepaper laid the foundation for a trustless digital\n    payment system. It introduced concepts like distributed ledgers (blockchains), mining, and incentivized validation that are now\n    standard across the cryptocurrency ecosystem.\n  </p>\n  <p class=\"text-red-200  indent-8\"> &#x27A1;<a href=\"https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-red-200  indent-8\"> Read the Bitcoin whitepaper </a>  </p>\n<br><br>\n\n <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> DOUBLE-SPENDING PROBLEM</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n<p>\n    Since the advent of digital technology, the double-spending problem has been a fundamental challenge preventing digital currency creation. It refers to the risk that a digital token could be copied and spent multiple times. Unlike physical cash, which can only be transferred once and cannot be used again by the sender, digital assets lack an inherent mechanism to prevent duplication without a central authority like a bank to track balances and transactions.\n<br><br>\n\nImagine sending someone \\$10 as an image via WhatsApp. The recipient sees it, but you still have the same image and can send it to someone else. This illustrates the core issue: without a trusted third party or reliable verification system, digital money is inherently vulnerable to fraud.\n<br><br>\n\nThe double-spending problem was one of the biggest barriers to creating viable digital currencies. Bitcoin\'s breakthrough was solving it without requiring a central authority. This innovation became the foundation for all modern cryptocurrencies.\n</p>\n </div>\n <br><br>\n\n\n  <h2>Tokenomics</h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin\'s economic model is deflationary, designed to create scarcity and long-term value preservation. It operates on a fixed\n    set of rules embedded in its protocol. These rules determine how new coins are created, how transactions are validated, and how incentives are distributed to network participants.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The key components of Bitcoin\'s tokenomics include:\n  </p>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside indent-4 pl-4 space-y-2\">\n    <li><strong>Maximum Supply:</strong> Bitcoin has a hardcoded maximum supply of 21 million BTC.</li>\n    <li><strong>Block Time:</strong> This is the average time required for the network to validate and add a new block of transactions to the blockchain. For Bitcoin, this is approximately 10 minutes.</li>\n    <li><strong>Reward Halving:</strong> The amount of BTC awarded to miners is halved at regular intervals, reducing the supply of new bitcoins entering the market. For Bitcoin, this occurs every 210,000 blocks (approximately 4 years). The current reward is 3.125 BTC.</li>\n    <li><strong>Mining Incentives:</strong> Miners are rewarded through a combination of block rewards and transaction fees.</li>\n    <li><strong>Deflationary Nature:</strong> Bitcoin\'s reduced issuance over time creates deflation. All Bitcoin is expected to be fully mined by 2140.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2> Adoption and Utility</h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin’s adoption has grown from a niche internet experiment to a globally recognized financial asset. Its decentralized\n    architecture appeals to both individual users seeking privacy and institutions seeking portfolio diversification, while its\n    utility extends beyond mere speculation, encompassing diverse financial applications, including:\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside  indent-4 pl-4 space-y-2\">\n    <li><strong>Retail:</strong> Adopted as a store of value, inflation hedge, and medium for digital payments.</li>\n    <li><strong>Institutional:</strong> Held by companies like MicroStrategy and Tesla, and by investment funds. Bitcoin is now integrated into ETFs and futures markets.</li>\n    <li><strong>Geopolitical:</strong> Used by citizens in inflation-prone countries; recognized as legal tender in El Salvador.</li>\n    <li><strong>Store of Value:</strong> Often referred to as \"digital gold\" due to its scarcity and decentralized nature.</li>\n    <li><strong>Medium of Exchange:</strong> Accepted by merchants and services; fast transactions enabled via the Lightning Network</li>\n    <li><strong>Remittance:</strong> Enables low-cost, borderless money transfers without centralized intermediaries.</li>\n    <li><strong>Collateral:</strong> Used in crypto lending platforms and decentralized finance (DeFi) products.</li>\n    <li><strong>Financial Sovereignty:</strong> Enables users to retain full control over their funds without relying on banks or governments.</li>\n    <li><strong>Market Impact:</strong> Bitcoin price movements often dictate overall cryptocurrency market trends.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> THE FUTURE OF BTC </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n    Bitcoin (BTC) is the first and most well-known cryptocurrency. It set the standard for decentralized digital finance and remains the benchmark against which all other cryptocurrencies are compared. Bitcoin continues to dominate financial markets with a historical pattern of approximately 100% price increase for every halving cycle, which occurs every four years. Unlike gold, Bitcoin has a fixed supply of 21 million coins, making it a truly deflationary asset.\n    The dominance of Bitcoin in the cryptocurrency market is expected to persist, as it maintains the largest market cap and liquidity among all cryptocurrencies.\n    </p>\n   </div>\n');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`material`) VALUES
('   <section>\n            <h2>Introduction to Altcoins</h2>\n            <p>\n                \"Altcoin\" is a portmanteau of \"alternative\" and \"coin.\" It refers to all cryptocurrencies other than Bitcoin. Since Bitcoin\'s launch in 2009, thousands of other cryptocurrencies have been developed with varying use cases, technologies, and communities. These are collectively referred to as altcoins (ALTs).\n                <br>\n                <br>\n          \n                Altcoins were created to address Bitcoin\'s technological limitations such as speed and energy consumption, experiment with new consensus mechanisms like Proof of Stake (PoS), enable new functionalities such as smart contracts and dApps, and serve specific niches like privacy, stable value, or governance.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        \n        <section>\n            <h2>The Role of Altcoins in Web3 and the Future</h2>\n                <p>\n                    Altcoins play a vital role in expanding the cryptocurrency ecosystem beyond Bitcoin.\n                    They offer innovation through new technologies, power decentralized applications, support DeFi\n                    and NFTs, and enable blockchain interoperability and governance. By diversifying use cases, altcoins drive adoption, competition, and continuous improvement within the Web3 space.\n                </p>\n                <br>\n            <p>\n                As blockchain technology evolves, altcoins will play increasingly important roles in digital economies and decentralized infrastructure.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <section>\n            <h2>Categories of Altcoins</h2>\n\n            <p>\n                Altcoins can be categorized based on their functionality, use cases, and underlying technology. Here is a simple table that places altcoins into different categories:\n            </p>\n            <br>\n\n           \n    <table class=\"min-w-full rounded-lg shadow-md\">\n      <thead>\n        <tr class=\"bg-gray-800 text-gray-300 uppercase text-sm\">\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Category</th>\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Examples</th>\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Use Cases</th>\n        </tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody class=\"text-gray-300\">\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Stablecoins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Tether (USDT), USD Coin (USDC), Binance USD (BUSD)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Stable trading, remittances, DeFi stability</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Utility Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Chainlink (LINK), Filecoin (FIL), Basic Attention Token (BAT)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Platform services and access</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Security Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">RWA tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Digital representation of real-world assets under regulatory compliance</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Governance Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Uniswap (UNI), Maker (MKR), Aave (AAVE)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">DAO voting and decision-making</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Privacy Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Monero (XMR), Zcash (ZEC), Dash (DASH)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Anonymous transactions</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Meme Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Dogecoin (DOGE), Shiba Inu (SHIB)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Tipping, community engagement, speculative trading</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Platform Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Ethereum (ETH), Cardano (ADA), Solana (SOL)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">dApps, smart contracts, NFT platforms</td>\n        </tr>\n\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n\n        </section>\n\n\n        <br>\n        <section>\n            <h2>Some popular Altcoins and their applications</h2>\n            <p>\n                Here are some of the most popular altcoins and their primary applications:  \n            </p>    \n                <ul class=\"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 \">\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Ethereum (ETH):</strong> The first platform to introduce smart contracts, enabling decentralized applications (dApps) and decentralized finance (DeFi).\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Binance Coin (BNB):</strong> Initially created as a utility token for the Binance exchange, it now powers the Binance Smart Chain for dApps and DeFi.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Cardano (ADA):</strong> A blockchain platform focused on sustainability, scalability, and interoperability, supporting smart contracts and dApps.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Solana (SOL):</strong> Known for its high throughput and low transaction costs, Solana is a platform for fast dApps and DeFi projects.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Polkadot (DOT):</strong> A multi-chain network that enables different blockchains to interoperate, facilitating cross-chain applications.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Ripple (XRP):</strong> Designed for fast and low-cost international money transfers, Ripple aims to revolutionize cross-border payments.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Chainlink (LINK):</strong> A decentralized oracle network that connects smart contracts with real-world data, enhancing their functionality.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Uniswap (UNI):</strong> A leading decentralized exchange (DEX) that allows users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets without intermediaries.\n                    </li>   \n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Dogecoin (DOGE):</strong> Originally created as a meme, Dogecoin has gained popularity for tipping and community engagement, with a strong online following.\n                    </li>   \n\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Litecoin (LTC):</strong> Often referred to as the silver to Bitcoin\'s gold, Litecoin is a peer-to-peer cryptocurrency designed for fast transactions.\n                    </li>\n                </ul>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        \n        <section>\n            <h2>Advantages of Altcoins</h2>\n            <ul class=\"list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-base indent-3\">\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Lower Entry Barriers:</strong> Altcoins often have a lower price per coin, making them more accessible to new and small-scale investors.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Broader Use Cases:</strong> Many altcoins are designed to serve specific functions, ranging from decentralized finance (DeFi) and smart contracts to privacy, gaming, and storage solutions.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Faster Technological Innovation:</strong> Altcoins push the boundaries of blockchain development by experimenting with new features and frameworks beyond what Bitcoin offers.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Higher Growth Potential:</strong> Being relatively new or undervalued, some altcoins offer substantial room for price appreciation and adoption.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>More Sustainable Consensus Models:</strong> Unlike Bitcoin\'s energy-intensive Proof of Work (PoW), many altcoins use energy-efficient models like Proof of Stake (PoS), reducing environmental impact.\n                    </li>\n                    </ul>\n<br><br>\n\n\n        <section>\n\n                    <h2>Risks and Challenges of Altcoins</h2>\n\n                <p>Altcoins offer innovation and investment opportunities, but they also come with significant risks and challenges that users, investors, and developers must carefully consider.</p>\n\n                <b>1. High Volatility</b>\n                <p>Altcoin prices can fluctuate dramatically within short periods due to low liquidity, speculative trading, and market sentiment. This makes them high-risk assets, especially for inexperienced investors.</p><br>\n\n                <b>2. Lack of Regulation</b>\n                <p>The regulatory landscape for altcoins is still evolving. Many projects operate in a legal gray area, making them susceptible to sudden bans, restrictions, or lawsuits, which can severely impact their value or usability.</p><br>\n\n                <b>3. Security Vulnerabilities</b>\n                <p>Altcoins, especially those from newer or less-experienced teams, may have exploitable code. Hacks, smart contract bugs, or poor security practices can lead to significant financial loss for users and investors.</p><br>\n\n                <b>4. Scams and Fraudulent Projects</b>\n                <p>With low barriers to entry, it\'s easy to launch altcoins without real utility. Pump-and-dump schemes, rug pulls, and fake ICOs have become common, leading to erosion of trust and investor losses.</p><br>\n\n                <b>5. Lack of Liquidity</b>\n                <p>Many altcoins are traded on fewer exchanges with limited volume. This makes it harder to buy or sell large amounts without significantly impacting the price, leading to slippage and poor trade execution.</p><br>\n\n                <b>6. Unproven Technology</b>\n                <p>Some altcoins use experimental consensus mechanisms or features that haven\'t been thoroughly tested at scale. As a result, they may face unexpected technical failures or require costly upgrades.</p><br>\n\n                <b>7. Market Saturation and Competition</b>\n                <p>The altcoin space is crowded, with thousands of coins competing for user adoption and capital. Most projects struggle to gain traction, and many eventually fade into obscurity or become abandoned.</p>\n\n                <b>8. Short Project Lifespans</b>\n                <p>A large percentage of altcoins are not maintained long-term. Teams may lose funding, shift focus, or dissolve, leaving holders with worthless or unsupported tokens.</p>\n\n                <b>9. Dependence on Community and Hype</b>\n                <p>Many altcoins derive their value from active communities or social media hype rather than utility or adoption. This makes them vulnerable to rapid sentiment shifts and price crashes.</p>\n\n                <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n                <p>Altcoins present exciting opportunities, but they are not without significant risks. Investors and users should conduct thorough research, diversify cautiously, and remain informed about market trends and project fundamentals. Understanding the potential pitfalls is essential for navigating the fast-evolving altcoin landscape responsibly.</p>\n\n        </section>\n\n<br><br>\n <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\">ALTCOIN HEADS UP</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n          Altcoins represent innovation, experimentation, and expansion in the cryptocurrency space.\n                While Bitcoin laid the foundation, altcoins push the boundaries of what blockchain technology can do.\n                Whether you\'re investing, building, or learning, understanding altcoins is essential to staying informed in the crypto world.\n         \n\n </div>\n<br><br>\n\n         <section>\n            <h2>Investing in Altcoins</h2>\n    <p>\n      Before investing in altcoins, it\'s important to approach with careful analysis and strategy. Consider the following key steps:\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <ol class=\"list-decimal list-inside space-y-3 text-base indent-3 \">\n      <li>\n        <strong>Evaluate the Project Team and Vision:</strong> Investigate the experience, credibility, and transparency of the development team. A strong, active team is often a good indicator of a project\'s long-term potential.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Read the Whitepaper and Understand the Tokenomics:</strong> Study the project’s goals, utility, supply distribution, and economic model to assess its real-world value and sustainability.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Analyze Market Capitalization and Trading Volume:</strong> Look beyond price. High market cap and strong trading volume often indicate healthy investor interest and liquidity.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Prioritize Security and Transparency:</strong> Ensure the project follows strong security protocols, has undergone audits, and communicates openly with its community.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Diversify Your Portfolio:</strong> Spread your investment across multiple credible projects to minimize risk and avoid overexposure to any single token.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Use Reputable Exchanges:</strong> Only buy and trade altcoins on trusted, secure, and well-regulated cryptocurrency exchanges to protect your assets.\n      </li>\n    </ol>\n\n        </section>\n\n        <br>\n'),
('   \n<p>The first practical step for anyone who is truly interested in crypto investing, after understanding the foundations of Web3 and cryptocurrencies, is to create and secure a wallet.\n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n  As explained earlier, a wallet is a digital tool that allows you to store, send, and receive cryptocurrencies.\n  There are two main types of wallets: software wallets (mobile or desktop applications) and\n  hardware wallets (physical devices).</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>\n    As a beginner, it is recommended to start with a software wallet because it is easier to use. Popular software wallets include MetaMask, Trust Wallet, and Coinbase Wallet.\n  </p>\n  \n  <br><br>\n\n  <b>Step 1: Choose a Wallet</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 list-inside \">\n    <li>Research and select a wallet that suits your needs (for this guide, we will use Trust Wallet as an example).</li>\n    <li>Wallets are available on different platforms, including mobile, desktop, and web versions.\n    The mobile version is installed on your phone as an app, the desktop version is installed on your computer, and the web version is accessed through your browser.</li>\n    <li>It is important to choose a wallet that is compatible with the cryptocurrencies you plan to use.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <b>Step 2: Download and Install</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Download and install the Trust Wallet application from the app store or the official website.</li>\n    <li>For mobile wallets, search for \"Trust Wallet\" in your app store (Google Play Store for Android or Apple App Store for iOS).</li>\n    <li>For desktop wallets, visit the official Trust Wallet website and download the appropriate version for your operating system (Windows, macOS, or Linux).</li>\n    <li>You can also install some wallets as browser extensions on desktop browsers.</li>\n    <li>Ensure you download the official version to avoid scams or phishing attempts.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <b>Step 3: Create a New Wallet</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Follow the instructions to create a new wallet.</li>\n    <li>This usually involves setting up a password and generating a recovery phrase.</li>\n    <li>Open the Trust Wallet app and select \"Create a New Wallet.\"</li>\n    <li>Read and accept the terms of service.</li>\n    <li>Set a strong password for your wallet. This password will be used to access your wallet and authorize transactions.</li>\n    <li>After setting the password, you will be presented with a recovery phrase (also known as a seed phrase).</li>\n    <li>Write down the recovery phrase in the correct order and store it securely.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <b>Step 4: Secure Your Wallet</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Write down your recovery phrase and store it in a safe place. This phrase is crucial for recovering your wallet if you lose access, and it must never be shared with anyone (this is very important!).</li>\n    <li>Do not store your recovery phrase digitally or online, as this can expose it to hackers.</li>\n    <li>Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) if available for added security.</li>\n    <li>Familiarize yourself with the wallet\'s security features, such as biometric authentication or PIN codes.</li>\n    <li>Always keep your wallet software updated to protect against vulnerabilities.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <b>Step 5: Fund Your Wallet</b>\n  <p>To start using your wallet, you need to add some cryptocurrency. The process of buying and adding crypto to your wallet will be discussed more broadly in subsequent lessons.</p>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <b>To send cryptocurrency, you will need the recipient\'s wallet address.</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Open your wallet app and navigate to the \"Send\" section.</li>\n    <li>Enter the recipient\'s wallet address, the amount you want to send, and any additional details required.</li>\n    <li>Review the transaction details and confirm the transaction.</li>\n    <li>Depending on the wallet, you may need to enter your password or use biometric authentication to authorize the transaction.</li>\n    <li>After confirming, the transaction will be processed, and you will receive a notification once it is completed.</li>\n    <li>You may be required to pay a transaction fee, which varies based on the network congestion and the cryptocurrency being sent.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <b>To receive cryptocurrency, you will share your wallet address with the sender.</b>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Open your wallet app and navigate to the \"Receive\" section.</li>\n    <li>Select the cryptocurrency you want to receive on the appropriate network (e.g., Ethereum, Bitcoin, etc.).</li>\n    <li>You will see your wallet address displayed as a string of characters or a QR code.</li>\n    <li>Copy your wallet address or scan the QR code provided.</li>\n    <li>Share this address with the person sending you cryptocurrency.</li>\n    <li>You can also buy cryptocurrency directly within the wallet app using a credit card or bank transfer, depending on the wallet\'s features and supported services.</li>\n    <li>You can purchase cryptocurrency from exchanges like Binance, Coinbase, or Kraken and transfer it to your wallet.</li>\n    <li>Follow the instructions on the exchange to deposit funds into your wallet address.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n\n\n  <h2>Note:</h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 list-inside\">\n    <li>Your wallet is like your bank account, while your wallet address is like your account number and can be shared with anyone.</li>\n    <li>Always double-check the wallet address before sending or receiving cryptocurrency to avoid mistakes, as transactions are irreversible.</li>\n    <li>Keep your wallet software updated to ensure you have the latest security features and improvements.</li>\n    <li>Write down your security phrase or seed phrase with pen and paper in the correct order, and protect it from others, because it is the key to your wallet. Anyone who has it can take your crypto.</li>\n    <li>Be cautious of phishing attempts and only download wallet software from official sources.</li>\n    <li>You can buy cryptocurrency from exchanges like Binance, Coinbase, or Kraken and transfer it to your wallet.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n\n  <p>This guide provides a basic overview of how to create and secure a cryptocurrency wallet using Trust Wallet as an example.</p>\n  <p>For more detailed instructions, refer to the official documentation of any wallet you plan to use.</p>\n  <br>\n  <p>This guide might look bulky and exhaustive on paper, but the process becomes much simpler and more natural in practice because it only takes a few clicks.</p>\n\n'),
('  \n<p>\n  \nFrom the previous lesson, you created an empty wallet that does not contain any crypto assets yet. Crypto assets can be received if someone sends them to your wallet address, or you can buy them with fiat on a crypto exchange and send them to your wallet.\n<br>\n\nBefore you proceed with buying and managing crypto, it is important to understand the risks and common mistakes beginners face when handling their assets.\n\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n  <h2>Common mistakes that beginners make</h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside space-y-2  indent-4\">\n    <li>\n      <b>Not backing up wallet seed phrase:</b>\n      Losing your recovery or seed phrase means permanent loss of access to your wallet. Storing it digitally (e.g., screenshots or cloud notes) makes it vulnerable to hacks, so always write it down on paper as soon as possible and store it securely.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Sharing private keys or seed phrases:</strong>\n      Your seed phrase is like a master key. Anyone with it can steal your funds. Never share it, even if someone claims to be \"Support\" or \"Admin,\" which is a common scam tactic on social media platforms like X (formerly Twitter).\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Falling for scams and phishing:</strong>\n      Fake wallet apps, websites, or giveaway scams are common. Always verify URLs and avoid clicking links in DMs or emails.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Investing without research (FOMO):</strong>\n      Many beginners are in a hurry to make money, so they buy coins simply because they are trending or heavily hyped. This fear of missing out often leads to poor decision-making. You need to stay calm, research, and understand a project\'s utility, team, and risks.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Sending funds to the wrong address or network:</strong>\n      Crypto transactions are irreversible. Sending funds to the wrong address or through an incompatible network can lead to permanent loss. Changing even a single character in an address can result in lost funds.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Investing more than they can afford to lose:</strong>\n      Crypto markets are volatile. Never invest emotionally or with money you cannot afford to lose. A token\'s past performance is not a guarantee of future results, because the crypto ecosystem is constantly changing.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Not understanding network fees:</strong>\n      Some networks have high gas fees, so unnecessarily transferring assets from one wallet to another is an easy way to lose money. Always check the fees before making transactions, consider using networks with lower fees for smaller transactions, and avoid unnecessary transfers.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Leaving funds on exchanges:</strong>\n      Centralized exchanges can be hacked, and they can also freeze withdrawals. Move your funds to a secure wallet if you are not actively trading or if you plan to hold for a long time. Always use reputable exchanges and enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Ignoring security best practices:</strong>\n            Not using 2FA, or using weak or reused passwords, puts your assets at risk.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Not understanding taxes or legal requirements:</strong>\n        In some countries and regions, crypto may be taxable. Beginners often fail to track their transactions properly, which can cause issues later.\n    </li>\n  </ol>\n\n<br><br>\n\n\n<div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> PHISHING SCAM </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      Phishing is a common tactic used by scammers to trick users into revealing sensitive information, such as private keys or seed phrases.\n    </p>\n      <br>\n    <p>\n      It involves scammers creating fake versions of popular websites and deceiving users into entering their credentials or wallet information on fraudulent platforms. For example, \"<b>https://metamask.io</b>\" is the official website of MetaMask, but a phishing site might look like \"<b>https://metamask-secure.com</b>\" or \"<b>https://metamask-login.com</b>\". These fake sites are designed to look exactly like the original, but they exist only to steal your information.\n    </p>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n          Always verify URLs, avoid clicking on suspicious links, and never share your private keys or seed phrases with anyone.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <p>If you receive an email claiming to be from your wallet provider and asking you to \"verify your account\" by entering your seed phrase, it is most likely a phishing attempt. Legitimate services will never ask for your seed phrase.</p>\n</div>\n'),
('\n <p>\n  Crypto is not like traditional banking, where you can call customer support to reverse a transaction or recover lost funds, so it is crucial to understand how to manage your assets properly and protect yourself from losses.\n  <br>\n  <br>\n  Crypto assets are primarily traded on two types of platforms: centralized platforms and decentralized platforms.\n  <br>\n  Centralized platforms require you to deposit your assets into their custody while they handle and process your transactions, whereas decentralized platforms allow you to retain full control of your assets in your wallet while making transactions.\n  \n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n  In this lesson, we will focus on decentralized platforms, and by the end of this session, you should have a solid understanding of decentralized exchanges and how to use them.\n  <br>\n  <br>\n </p>\n<br>\n\n\n<h2>Decentralized Exchange</h2>\n    \n <p>\n     In the context of crypto asset management, decentralization removes reliance on intermediaries and focuses on user autonomy.\n     <br>\n     As an analogy, decentralization simply means having your money in your own hands and under your control, without depositing it in a bank that can decide the terms of your spending or question your financial activities. In the same way, when your assets are in your wallet, you have full control, you can send or receive tokens, and you are free to interact with Web3 applications.\n      <br>\n      <br>\n\n    </p>\n\n<p>\n\n      A decentralized exchange (DEX) is a platform that allows you to trade cryptocurrencies directly from your wallet without the need for a central authority or intermediary. DEXs operate on blockchain technology, enabling peer-to-peer transactions while still allowing you to maintain 100% control over your funds.\n      <br>\n      <br>\n\n      To trade on a DEX, you simply visit its website or download its application, connect your wallet, select the tokens you want to trade, then sign and execute the transaction. The process is automated through smart contracts, which handle trade execution and settlement.\n      <br>\n    </p>\n   \n<br>\n<br>\n  <h2>Decentralized trading (Swapping)</h2>\n\n  <p>Decentralized exchanges (DEXs) are a key component of this ecosystem, allowing users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets without giving custody to a third party. Trading on DEXs is known as swapping. Platforms like Uniswap, PancakeSwap, and SushiSwap operate using smart contracts deployed on public blockchains. All you have to do is connect your wallet and sign transactions to buy or sell tokens.\n  </p> \n\n  <br><br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> SWAPPING </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      Swapping is the process of exchanging one cryptocurrency for another directly on a decentralized exchange (DEX). Unlike traditional exchanges, DEXs allow users to trade directly from their wallets. This process is facilitated by smart contracts that automate trade execution, ensuring transparency and security.\n      <br>\n      <br>\n      In practical terms, swapping is simply buying and selling happening at the same time. What matters is the final token you hold after the transaction.\n      <br>\n      <b><i>For example, </i></b>if you swap 1 ETH for 200 USDT, you are effectively selling 1 ETH and buying 200 USDT. Conversely, if you swap 200 USDT for 1 ETH, you are selling 200 USDT and buying 1 ETH.\n      <br>\n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br>\n\n  <p>Key aspects of decentralized exchanges include:\n  <ol class=\"list-none list-inside space-y-2 indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Peer-to-peer trading:</strong> Users can interact directly with each other via automated protocols, without intermediaries.</li>\n    <li><strong>Smart contracts:</strong> All trading logic and asset swaps are governed by transparent, tamper-proof code rather than human administrators.</li>\n    <li><strong>User custody:</strong> Traders retain full control over their assets throughout the entire process.</li>\n    <li><strong>Open-source transparency:</strong> Many DEX platforms are built on open-source software, allowing public audits and community contributions.</li>\n  </ol>\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>By decentralizing exchange and trading infrastructure, DEXs reduce the risks of hacks, fund freezes, and market manipulation that are more common in centralized systems.</p>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2>Benefits of trading on DEXs</h2>\n  \n  <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 indent-4 pl-4\">\n    <li><strong>Self-sovereignty:</strong> Users have complete ownership and control of their digital assets.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Reduced counterparty risk:</strong> Since no third party holds the assets, there is less risk of loss due to institutional failure.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Global accessibility:</strong> Anyone with internet access and a supported wallet can participate, regardless of geographic location or financial background.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Interoperability:</strong> Decentralized finance (DeFi) protocols allow users to lend, borrow, stake, and earn yields directly from their wallets without needing a bank or asset manager.</li>\n  <li>\n    <strong>Governance and Community Participation : </strong>\n    As an investor in a governance token, keeping your tokens in your wallet allows you to vote on key proposals such as upgrades, fund allocation, and strategic direction.\n  </li>\n  </ol>\n\n\n\n  <br><br>\n  <h2> Challenges of DEX trading </h2>\n  <p>While powerful, DEXs also come with some challenges:</p>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 indent-4 pl-4\">\n    <li><strong>User responsibility:</strong> Without custodians, users are fully responsible for their own security. Mistakes can lead to irreversible loss of funds.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Complex interfaces:</strong> Some DEX platforms are less user-friendly than centralized ones, which can discourage newcomers. However, DEXs are becoming easier to use every day.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Scalability and speed:</strong> Decentralized networks may experience congestion and high transaction fees during peak demand.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Regulatory uncertainty:</strong> The decentralized nature of these platforms makes it difficult for regulators to apply traditional frameworks, which can lead to legal ambiguity.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>As blockchain technology continues to evolve, DEXs will remain central to its progress, offering a platform where users have full control and do not have to expose their personal data just to make a simple trade.</p>\n\n \n  \n'),
('\n  <h2>What is a Centralised Exchange?</h2>\n  <p>A Centralised Exchange (CEX) is a platform operated by a company or organization that acts as a middleman between buyers and sellers of cryptocurrency. These platforms handle transactions, user accounts, and security on behalf of users.</p>\n<br>\n  <p>They serve as a bridge between cryptocurrency and traditional finance. Think of a CEX like a bank or a stock exchange. In crypto terms, when you use a CEX, you are trusting the exchange to hold your assets, keep them safe, and process your trades.</p>\n\n  <p><strong>Popular examples of centralised exchanges are:</strong></p>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside\">\n    <li>Binance</li>\n    <li>Coinbase</li>\n    <li>Kraken</li>\n    <li>KuCoin</li>\n    <li>Gate.io</li>\n    <li>OKX</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>These platforms are often the first place new users go to buy or trade cryptocurrencies because they provide a simple way to buy, sell, and trade digital assets using traditional currencies like USD, EUR, or GBP. They also offer user-friendly interfaces and handle most of the technical aspects of trading for you.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2> How do Centralised Exchanges work </h2>\n\n  <p>Centralised exchanges operate by matching buy and sell orders from users. Here\'s a simplified breakdown of how they work:</p>\n  <ol class=\"list-none indent-4  list-inside  space-y-2 \" >\n    <li><strong>Order Matching:</strong> When you place an order to buy or sell crypto, the exchange matches it with another user\'s order.</li>\n    <li><strong>Custodial Services:</strong> The exchange holds your crypto in its wallets, managing the private keys for you.</li>\n    <li><strong>Trading Fees:</strong> CEXs charge fees for trades, deposits, and withdrawals, which can vary widely.</li>\n    <li><strong>Security Measures:</strong> They implement various security protocols to protect user funds, but they are still vulnerable to hacks.</li> \n    <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Many CEXs comply with local regulations, requiring KYC (Know Your Customer) verification.</li>\n  </ol>\n  \n\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2> Step-by-step guide to getting started with a CEX </h2>\n\n\n  <p>Using a centralised exchange is generally straightforward. Here\'s a step-by-step guide to get you started:</p>\n  <br>\n\n<section class=\"pl-5\">   \n  <b>1. Choose a Reputable Exchange</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Start by selecting a well-known and reputable centralised exchange. Look for reviews, security features, and user feedback. Some of the most popular options are listed above.</p>\n  <br>\n  <b>2. Create an Account</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Sign up for an account on the exchange. For this, you will need to provide and verify your email address and create a strong password.</p>\n  <br>  \n  <b>3. Complete KYC Verification</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Most exchanges require you to complete KYC (Know Your Customer) verification. This usually involves submitting an identification document such as a passport, driver\'s license, national identity document, or bank-issued identification number, and sometimes proof of address. All of this is done in compliance with government regulations and anti-money laundering measures.</p>\n  <br>\n  <b>4. Secure Your Account</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security. This adds an extra layer of protection to your account, making it harder for unauthorized users to access it.</p>\n  <br>\n  <b>5. Deposit Funds</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Once your account is set up, you can deposit funds. Most exchanges allow you to deposit fiat currency (like USD, EUR, etc.) via bank transfer, credit card, or other payment methods like P2P. They also accept cryptocurrency deposits if you already own crypto.</p>  \n  <br>\n\n  <b>6. Start Trading</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">With funds in your account, you can start trading. You can buy or sell various cryptocurrencies by placing orders on the exchange. You can choose between market orders (buy/sell at the current market price) or limit orders (set a specific price for buying or selling).</p>\n  <br>\n  <b>7. Withdraw Funds</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">After trading, you can withdraw your funds. If you want to take your crypto off the exchange, you can transfer it to your personal wallet. If you want to cash out, you can withdraw fiat currency back to your bank account.</p>\n  <br>\n  <b>8. Monitor Your Account</b>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Regularly check your account for updates, security alerts, or policy changes. It\'s also a good idea to keep track of your trades and balances.</p>\n\n</section>\n<br>\n\n\n  <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> CUSTODIANSHIP: WHO HOLDS MY CRYPTO </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n       <p>When you use a CEX, your crypto is stored by the exchange, not in your personal wallet. You do not hold your private keys, meaning that if the exchange is hacked or shuts down, you might lose access.</p>\n       <br>\n  <p>This leads to the saying: <b>\"Not your keys, not your coins.\"</b></p>\n  </div>\n  <br><br>\n  \n  \n\n\n  <h2> Benefits of using Centralised Exchanges </h2>\n  <br>\n    <p>Centralised exchanges offer several advantages that make them appealing to both new and experienced traders. Below are some of these benefits:</p>\n    <br>\n    <section class=\"pl-5\">\n    <h3><strong>1. User-Friendly Interface</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Centralised exchanges (CEXs) are designed with simplicity in mind, making them ideal for beginners. Most offer clean dashboards, mobile apps, and guided features like instant buy/sell buttons. This makes it easy to start trading without needing to understand the complex technical details of blockchain technology.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>2. High Liquidity</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Liquidity refers to how easily an asset can be bought or sold without causing a major change in its price. Centralised exchanges usually have a large number of users and high trading volume, which means you can execute trades quickly and at more stable prices, especially for assets with high demand.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>3. Fiat Support</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Most CEXs allow users to fund their accounts using traditional fiat currencies like USD, EUR, or NGN. This means you can buy crypto directly using your debit card, bank transfer, or mobile money, a convenience not always available on decentralized platforms.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>4. Customer Support</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">If you run into issues like a failed transaction, login problems, or withdrawal delays, centralised exchanges typically provide customer support via live chat, email, or help tickets. This level of service is especially helpful for users who are not technically inclined.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>5. Advanced Trading Tools</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">For more experienced users, centralised platforms often offer sophisticated tools such as:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Real-time charts</li>\n        <li>Limit and stop orders</li>\n        <li>Futures and margin trading</li>\n        <li>API access for bots</li>\n    </ol>\n    <p class=\"pl-5\">These tools make it easier to implement complex trading strategies and monitor the market effectively.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>6. Security Infrastructure</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Top-tier centralised exchanges invest heavily in security. They use advanced measures such as:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)</li>\n        <li>Cold wallet storage</li>\n        <li>Regular security audits</li>\n    </ol>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">While no system is completely risk-free, these platforms typically offer stronger protective infrastructure than individual users managing their own wallets.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h3><strong>7. Regulatory Compliance</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Many centralised exchanges comply with local regulations, which can provide an added layer of trust. They often require KYC (Know Your Customer) verification, which helps prevent fraud and money laundering. This compliance can also make it easier to resolve disputes in some cases.</p>\n    </section>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong> Risks and downsides of Centralised Exchanges</strong></h2>\n  <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>1. Lack of full control</strong>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">On centralised exchanges, you do not control your private keys; the exchange does. This means you rely entirely on the platform to access and manage your funds.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>2. Security breaches</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Exchanges are common targets for hackers due to the large volume of funds they hold. If hacked, users can lose their assets, often with little chance of recovery.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>3. Regulatory risks</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Governments can suddenly change crypto regulations. This may lead to account freezes, trading bans, or forced shutdowns of exchanges, especially in certain regions.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>4. Withdrawal restrictions</strong></h3>\n    <p  class=\"pl-4\">Exchanges may impose limits on how much you can withdraw daily. Delays or freezes can also occur during system issues, audits, or flagged account activity.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>5. Custodial risk</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Your assets are held by the exchange, and mismanagement, fraud, or bankruptcy (like the FTX case) can result in total loss of funds, with no guaranteed compensation.</p>\n\n<br><br>\n\n  <p>Centralised exchanges are an essential entry point for most crypto beginners. They offer convenience, ease of use, and access to fiat on-ramps, all of which are crucial for getting started.</p>\n  <p>However, as you grow in the crypto space, you will begin to understand their limitations and gradually explore decentralized options where you can fully own and safely manage your assets.</p>\n  \n');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`material`) VALUES
('    <section >\n            <h2>What is an Order?</h2>\n            <p>An order is an instruction you give to an exchange to buy or sell an asset at a specific price and quantity. All trades on centralized exchanges (CEXs) begin with placing an order, which goes into an order book where buyers and sellers are matched.</p>\n        </section>\n<br>\n        <section>\n            <h2>Types of Orders</h2>\n\n            <div class=\"p-3 rounded-lg shadow mb-2\">\n                <b>1. Market Order</b>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order executes immediately at the best available price. It is very useful for quick trades, but it may experience price slippage.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\" p-3 rounded-lg shadow mb-2\">\n                <b>2. Limit Order</b>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order lets you set the price and quantity at which you want to buy or sell. The order remains on the book until your set price is reached and your order is matched.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\" p-3 rounded-lg shadow mb-2\">\n                <b>3. Stop Order (Stop-Loss)</b>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order triggers a market order when the asset reaches a specific price. It is widely used to reduce losses or enter trends.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\"p-3 rounded-lg shadow\">\n                <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold \">4. Stop-Limit Order</h3>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">Triggers a limit order instead of a market order once the stop price is hit. Offers more control but might not be filled.</p>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n<br>\n\n\n        <section class=\"mb-6\">\n            <h2 class=\" mb-2\">Order duration</h2>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">Order duration is simply the lifetime of an order, or the timed condition that determines whether an order will be executed, cancelled, or expired. They are classified as:</p>\n\n            <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside pl-4\">\n                <li><b>GTC (Good Till Cancelled):</b> Stays active until filled or manually canceled.</li>\n                <li><b>IOC (Immediate or Cancel):</b> Fills what it can instantly, and cancels the rest.</li>\n                <li><b>FOK (Fill or Kill):</b> Must fill the entire order immediately or cancel it all.</li>\n            </ol>\n            <br>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">\n              <b class=\"text-red-100\">NOTE </b> : Orders are automatically set to GTC by default, meaning they will remain open until filled or canceled. You can change this setting in your exchange account preferences.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <section class=\"mb-6\">\n              <section >\n            <h2>Order books</h2>\n            <p>The order book is a live record of all open buy and sell orders. Buy orders are called <em>bids</em>, while sell orders are called <em>asks</em>. The exchange\'s matching engine finds matching pairs and executes trades automatically.</p>\n        </section>\n<br>\n\n            <b>Sample order book</b>\n            <div class=\"overflow-x-auto\">\n                <table class=\"w-full text-sm text-left border border-gray-300\">\n                    <thead>\n                        <tr>\n                            <th class=\"px-3 py-2\">Buy Orders (Bids)</th>\n                            <th></th>\n                            <th class=\"px-3 py-2\">Sell Orders (Asks)</th>\n                        </tr>\n                    </thead>\n                    <tbody>\n                        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$29,950 - 0.5 BTC</td>\n                            <td></td>\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$30,000 - 0.7 BTC</td>\n                        </tr>\n                        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$29,900 - 1.0 BTC</td>\n                            <td></td>\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$30,100 - 1.2 BTC</td>\n                        </tr>\n                    </tbody>\n                </table>\n            </div>\n            <p class=\"mt-2 dark:text-gray-400\">This is a simplified view of an order book. The left side shows buy orders (bids), while the right side shows sell orders (asks). On an exchange, the price and quantity of each order are usually displayed side by side with the order request form <span class=\"text-red-100\"><i><a href=\"#demo_box\">(Demo shown below)</a></i></span></p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        <br>\n\n\n\n\n        <section>\n            <h2> Steps to placing an Order </h2>\n        <p>Placing an order on a centralized exchange is straightforward. Follow these steps to help ensure your trades are executed correctly:</p>\n        <br>\n       \n        <div class=\" mx-auto\">\n        <!-- Step 1 -->\n            <section class=\"mb-1\">\n                <b>1. Choose the asset to trade</b>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">Select the cryptocurrency or trading pair you want to trade, such as <strong>BTC/USDT</strong> or <strong>ETH/USDT</strong>. Ensure the market has sufficient liquidity and matches your trading goals.</p>\n            </section>\n            <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 2 -->\n        <section>\n            <b>2. Select the order type</b>\n            <p  class=\"pl-3\">Pick how you want the order to execute:</p>\n            <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside mt-2 pl-3\">\n                <li><b>Market Order:</b> Fills immediately at the best available price.</li>\n                <li><b>Limit Order:</b> Executes only at your specified price or better.</li>\n                <li><b>Stop Order:</b> Triggers when a target price is reached.</li>\n                <li><b>Stop-Limit Order:</b> Converts into a limit order after the stop price is hit.</li>\n            </ol>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 3 -->\n        <section>\n            <b>3. Enter price and amount</b>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">Enter the <strong>price</strong> (for non-market orders) and the <strong>amount</strong> of the asset you want to buy or sell. Most exchanges will calculate the total cost or proceeds automatically.</p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 4 -->\n        <section>\n            <b>4. Review order details</b>\n            <p  class=\"pl-3\">Check all inputs carefully before submitting:</p>\n            <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside mt-2 pl-3\">\n                <li>Buy or Sell side</li>\n                <li>Order type</li>\n                <li>Trading pair</li>\n                <li>Price, amount, and estimated total</li>\n                <li>Applicable fees</li>\n            </ol>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 5 -->\n        <section>\n            <b>5. Submit and monitor the order</b>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">Submit your order. Market orders are executed instantly, while limit and stop orders remain open until they are filled. Monitor active orders under <strong>\"Open Orders\"</strong> and track completed trades in your order history. You can cancel or adjust unfilled orders if needed.</p>\n        </section>\n        </div>\n\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        \n        <section>\n            <p> <i></i>   Orders are the backbone of trading on centralized exchanges. Whether you are trading as a beginner or as an experienced user, understanding how market, limit, stop, and other types of orders work will give you more control and help reduce unnecessary losses. Use the tools provided by your CEX wisely so you can trade safely and efficiently.           \n            </p>\n           \n        </section>\n<br>\n <br>\n            <p class=\"text-red-500 font-italic text-center\">Below is a simple demo order form.</p>\n    <div class=\"max-w-md mx-auto mt-10 p-6 dark:bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md\" id=\"demo_box\">\n        <h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-center\">  Place order  <span class=\"text-blue-500\"><b> (DEMO) </b> </span>  </h2>\n\n        <form method=\"POST\" class=\"space-y-4\">\n\n            <!-- Order Side: Buy or Sell -->\n            <div class=\"flex justify-between bg-gray-100 p-2 rounded-lg\">\n                <label class=\"w-1/2 text-center\">\n                    <input type=\"radio\" name=\"side\" value=\"buy\" class=\"hidden peer\" checked>\n                    <div class=\"peer-checked:bg-green-500 peer-checked:text-white p-2 rounded-lg cursor-pointer\">Buy</div>\n                </label>\n                <label class=\"w-1/2 text-center\">\n                    <input type=\"radio\" name=\"side\" value=\"sell\" class=\"hidden peer\">\n                    <div class=\"peer-checked:bg-red-500 peer-checked:text-white p-2 rounded-lg cursor-pointer\">Sell</div>\n                </label>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Order Type: Market or Limit -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"order_type\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Order Type</label>\n                <select name=\"order_type\" id=\"order_type\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n                    <option value=\"market\">Market</option>\n                    <option value=\"limit\">Limit</option>\n                </select>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Trading Pair -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"pair\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Trading Pair</label>\n                <select name=\"pair\" id=\"pair\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n                    <option value=\"BTC/USDT\">BTC/USDT</option>\n                    <option value=\"ETH/USDT\">ETH/USDT</option>\n                    <option value=\"BNB/USDT\">BNB/USDT</option>\n                </select>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Price Field (for Limit Orders) -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"price\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Price (USDT)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.01\" name=\"price\" id=\"price\" placeholder=\"Enter price\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Amount Field -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"amount\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Amount (e.g., BTC)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.0001\" name=\"amount\" id=\"amount\" placeholder=\"Enter amount\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Optional: Auto-Calculated Total -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"total\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Total (USDT)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.01\" name=\"total\" id=\"total\" placeholder=\"Auto-calculated or manual\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Submit Button -->\n            <div>\n                <button type=\"submit\" class=\"w-full py-2 px-4 bg-blue-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-md hover:bg-blue-700\" disabled>Submit Order</button>\n            </div>\n        </form>\n    </div>\n\n\n  \n'),
('    <div>\n\n        <p class=\"mb-6\">In the world of cryptocurrency, an airdrop refers to the distribution of free tokens or coins to a large number of wallet addresses. This is often done as a promotional strategy by blockchain projects to create awareness, reward users, build a loyal community, or decentralize token ownership.</p>\n\n        <p class=\"mb-6\">Simply put, airdrops are a way to give free crypto assets to users, either automatically or in exchange for small tasks, in an effort to build engagement and interest in a project.</p>\n\n    <h2>Why do crypto projects perform airdrops?</h2>\n    <p>Airdrops serve several purposes in the cryptocurrency ecosystem, including but not limited to:</p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"indent-4 list-[lower-roman] mb-6 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li><b>Marketing and awareness:</b> Airdrops create buzz and bring attention to a new crypto project.</li>\n        <li><b>Rewarding loyalty:</b> Existing users or community members are often rewarded for their support.</li>\n        <li><b>Decentralized token distribution:</b> It serves as a way to spread token ownership across a wide audience.</li>\n        <li><b>Kickstarting ecosystems:</b> Encourages early adoption and use of a platform or blockchain.</li>\n    </ol>\n    \n    <br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> IMPORTANCE OF AIRDROPS </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        The importance of airdrops in building a user base cannot be overstated. This importance stems from the fact that money is a shared belief and is only accepted as money because many people believe it has value and respect its worth.\n\n        Every new cryptocurrency project aims to establish a user base that believes in its value and potential. Airdrops provide an effective way to achieve this by distributing free tokens to users, thereby encouraging them to engage with the platform.\n        By receiving tokens, users are more likely to explore the project, participate in its ecosystem, and spread the word to others. This creates a ripple effect, attracting more users and building a community around the project.\n        \n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br><br>\n\n\n\n    <h2>Common types of airdrops</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Airdrops can take various forms, each with its own criteria depending on the goal the developers want to achieve. Here are some common types of airdrops you might encounter:\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] pl-3 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li><b>Standard airdrop:</b> Users receive tokens just for signing up or providing their wallet address.</li>\n        <li><b>Bounty airdrop:</b> Users complete specific tasks like sharing posts, joining groups, or creating content.</li>\n        <li><b>Holder airdrop:</b> Tokens are given to holders of another cryptocurrency, such as ETH or a specific token.</li>\n        <li><b>Exclusive airdrop:</b> Sent to selected users, often based on previous involvement with the project.</li>\n        <li><b>Retroactive airdrop:</b> Rewards users who have already interacted with a platform before a certain date.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n\n\n    <h2>How airdrops work</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Airdrops typically follow a structured process to ensure fair distribution and engagement. Here\'s how they generally work:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] pl-3 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li>The project announces an upcoming airdrop and defines the eligibility rules. This is usually done through its social media handles and is often promoted further by influencers.</li>\n        <li>Users may need to complete tasks such as following social media accounts, joining Telegram groups, or holding specific tokens in their wallets.</li>\n        <li>A snapshot may be taken on the blockchain at a specific time to record wallet balances.</li>\n        <li>Eligible users may need to complete tasks or simply wait to receive the tokens.</li>\n        <li>The tokens are then distributed automatically or made claimable through a link.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n    <b>How to qualify for airdrops</b>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">To qualify for airdrops, users typically need to meet certain criteria set by the project\'s developers. Some users may be left out if they do not meet those requirements. Here are some common ways to become eligible:</p>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li>Interact with DeFi platforms, bridges, or testnets.</li>\n        <li>Hold specific tokens or NFTs in non-custodial wallets.</li>\n        <li>Participate early in a protocol\'s ecosystem.</li>\n        <li>Stay informed through official project channels and community forums.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n\n    <h2>Classes of airdrops</h2>\n    <p>\n        Airdrops can also be categorized into different classes based on the tasks performed. Here are some common classes of airdrops:\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Testnets</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Testnets are networks used for testing before launching on the mainnet. Airdrops on testnets reward users who interact with the platform during its development phase.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Retroactive Airdrops</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Retroactive airdrops reward users who previously interacted with a platform, even before its official launch. This encourages early adoption and community engagement.</p>\n    <br>    \n    <h4><strong>Yapping</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Yapping refers to airdrops that require users to engage in social media activities, such as sharing posts, joining groups, or creating content. This helps increase the project\'s visibility and reach.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><Strong>DEPIN</Strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">DEPIN (Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks) airdrops are designed to reward users who contribute to the development of decentralized physical infrastructure. This can include tasks like running nodes, providing resources, or participating in governance.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Mining</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Mining airdrops are distributed to users who contribute computational power to secure the network. This is common in proof-of-work blockchains, where miners are rewarded with tokens for validating transactions and maintaining the network.</p>\n    <br>\n\n\n\n    <h2>Risks and cautions</h2>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-4 list-inside space-y-2 \">\n        <li><strong>Phishing Scams:</strong> Beware of fake airdrops asking for private keys or wallet access.</li>\n        <li><strong>Dusting Attacks:</strong> Some fake tokens may be sent to wallets to track or exploit users.</li>\n        <li><strong>Privacy Risks:</strong> Sharing wallet addresses or linking social media can expose personal data.</li>\n        <li><strong>Tax Liabilities:</strong> Airdropped tokens may be considered taxable income in some jurisdictions.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <b>Examples of famous Airdrops</b>\n    <ol class=\"pl-4 list-disc space-y-2 list-inside \">\n        <li><b>Uniswap (UNI):</b> Gave away 400 UNI tokens to every wallet that used the platform before a certain date.</li>\n        <li><b>Arbitrum (ARB):</b> Rewarded users who interacted with the Arbitrum Layer 2 network.</li>\n        <li><b>Optimism (OP):</b> Airdropped tokens to early users of the Optimism ecosystem.</li>\n        <li><b>Aptos (APT):</b> Distributed tokens to users who participated in the Aptos testnet.</li>\n        <li><b>StarkNet (STRK):</b> Airdropped tokens to users who engaged with the StarkNet Layer 2 solution.</li>\n\n    </ol>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <p>Airdrops offer a unique opportunity to earn free tokens and get involved in early-stage crypto projects. While they can be highly rewarding, users must stay vigilant and protect themselves from scams and malicious actors. By understanding how airdrops work and how to qualify safely, traders and enthusiasts can take advantage of them and earn without needing investment capital. If tasks are required, simply complete them and remain patient.</p>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        Airdrops are a good entry point for crypto enthusiasts who do not yet have capital for investments.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        <b>DISCLAIMER</b> Always do your own research (DYOR) before participating in airdrops. Only use official channels and never share your private keys or sensitive information with anyone. Airdrops are not guaranteed and may involve risks, including the potential loss of funds.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <p><a href=\"https://t.me/+9_JSb04pVRsyNjc8\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-300\"><i>(Click to join our official airdrops advisory telegram group)</i></a></p>\n\n</div>\n<br>\n    \n    \n'),
('<h2> Intro </h2>\n<p>\n   Because airdrops use different tools depending on their class, this session provides practical steps for participating in them and benefiting from them.\n</p>\n<br>\n<section>\n\n<h2>Testnets</h2>\n<p class=\"pl-3\">\n    Testnets are networks used for testing purposes before launching on the mainnet. Airdrops on testnets reward users who interact with the platform during its development phase. This is a common way to engage early adopters and gather feedback before the official launch.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n</p>\n\n\n\n    <b class=\"text-lg\">Testnet tools/process</b>\n<p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Visit the website and connect your burner wallet on the testnet\'s preferred network.</li>\n        <li>Get testnet tokens. The testnet guidelines should explain how to obtain them.</li>\n        <li>Interact with the platform by performing actions like sending and receiving tokens across wallets, trading, providing liquidity, swapping testnet tokens, bridging between networks, staking, or using specific features.</li>\n        </li>\n        <li>Complete any required tasks or forms to qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n        <li>Wait for the snapshot date to see whether you qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n</p>\n<p class=\"pl-3\">\n    <strong>NOTE:</strong> If you are using a mobile device, it is best to open the built-in browser of your wallet app, such as Trust Wallet or MetaMask, to access the testnet\'s website. This helps ensure that your wallet is properly connected and can interact smoothly with the testnet\'s features.\n</p>\n\n</section>\n\n<br><br>\n\n<section>\n    <h2>Yapping</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Yapping is a term used to describe the process of engaging with a project on social media platforms to qualify for an airdrop. This typically involves following the project\'s official accounts, sharing posts, joining community groups, and completing other social tasks as specified by the project.\n        Yapping is often a requirement for users to prove their interest in and support for the project, which can help increase the project\'s visibility and community engagement.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <b class=\"text-lg \">Yapping tools/process</b>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n            <li>Create dedicated non-personal social media accounts on Twitter, Reddit, Medium, and Facebook.</li>\n            <li>Stay active by posting content that reflects your interests, maintain visibility, and grow your Twitter page to at least 500 followers. Get verified if you can, although verification is not necessary.</li>\n            <li>Go to the project\'s website, create an account, and connect your Twitter account.</li>\n            <li>Follow the project\'s official social media accounts (Twitter, Telegram, Discord, etc.).</li>\n            <li>Post or retweet specific content as instructed by the project using the required tags and hashtags.</li>\n            <li>Get updates about the project by joining community groups and participating in discussions.</li>\n            <li>Complete any additional tasks such as filling out forms or creating content.</li>\n            <li>Invite and onboard new users using your referral links to increase your earnings.</li>\n            <li>Wait for the airdrop announcement to see whether you qualify.</li>\n        </ol>\n    </p>\n\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <strong>NOTE:</strong> Yapping is a common requirement for many airdrops, and it helps projects build a community of engaged users. However, it is important to be cautious and avoid spammy behavior, such as repeatedly posting the same content, because this can lead to account suspensions or bans on social media platforms.\n        <br>\n        Always follow the project\'s guidelines and engage genuinely with the community.\n    </p>\n\n</section>\n<br>\n<br>\n\n\n<section>\n    <h2>DEPINs</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        DEPINs, or Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks, are a class of airdrops that reward users for contributing to the development of decentralized physical infrastructure. This can include tasks like running nodes, providing resources, or participating in governance.\n        DEPINs aim to create a more resilient and decentralized network by incentivizing users to contribute to the physical infrastructure that supports blockchain networks.\n        <br>\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <h3 class=\"text-lg pl-3 font-bold \">DEPINs tools/process</h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-5\">\n        <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n            <li>Identify a DEPIN project that interests you and has an active community.</li>\n            <li>Join the project\'s community channels (Discord, Telegram, etc.) to stay updated.</li>\n            <li>Run a node or provide resources as required by the project. This is usually done by downloading and installing certain applications or browser extensions on your device and keeping it connected to the internet, so your device will keep running for the project.</li>\n            <li>Participate in governance decisions if applicable.</li>\n            <li>Stick to the project\'s guidelines, and do not try to game or cheat the system.</li>\n            <li>Complete any additional tasks that are regularly announced to qualify.</li>\n            <li>Invite and onboard new users using your referral links to increase your earnings.</li>\n            <li>Wait for the snapshot date to see whether you qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n        </ol>\n    </p>\n</section>\n<br>\n<br>\n\n<section>\n    <h2>Important tips about airdrops</h2>\n  <section class=\"pl-3\">\n    <p>\n      <strong>i. </strong>  Airdrops are not guaranteed, and the amount of tokens received can vary based on the project\'s criteria and your level of participation. Always do your own research (DYOR) before engaging in any airdrop activities, and be cautious of scams or phishing attempts.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>ii. </strong>\n        Airdrops require patience and consistent engagement with the project because some can go on for years. It is important to stay informed about the project\'s updates, participate in community discussions, and complete tasks as required to maximize your chances of receiving tokens.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>iii. </strong>\n        Airdrops can be a side job because they can be done from anywhere, at any time, and with little to no investment. However, they require dedication and a willingness to learn about different projects and their ecosystems.\n        <br>    \n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>iv. </strong>\n        DEPINs can weaken your device if you are not careful, as they require your device to remain connected to the internet and keep running applications that may consume significant resources. It is important to monitor your device\'s performance and ensure it can handle the demands of running a node or providing resources. If it cannot, then do not continue.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>v. </strong>\n        Always be cautious of scams and phishing attempts in the crypto space. Only participate in airdrops from reputable projects. Airdrops that ask you for any form of payment are a red flag and, most of the time, are not genuine. Use official channels to verify the legitimacy of airdrop announcements, and never share your private keys or sensitive information with anyone.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>vi. </strong>\n        To claim your rewards, the project will announce how rewards will be distributed to participants. This may involve submitting a wallet address from an exchange or claiming on-chain to your connected wallet, which may require gas fees.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n</section>\n</section>\n\n'),
('  <p>Crypto trading refers to the process of buying and selling cryptocurrencies with the aim of making a profit. Similar to stock trading, it involves speculating on the price movements of digital assets such as Bitcoin<strong>(BTC)</strong>, Ethereum<strong>(ETH)</strong>, Solana<strong>(SOL)</strong>, and many others.</p>\n      <br>\n\n      <p> The value of a crypto asset is determined by supply and demand in the open market, while supply and demand are influenced by technological developments, regulatory news, market sentiment, macroeconomic factors, and more. Profitable crypto trading is therefore a special skill that is developed through conscious effort and dedication to the crypto ecosystem.</p>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2>Trading/Currency pairs</h2>\n\n    <p> Trading pairs are combinations of two different currencies that can be traded for each other on an exchange. They represent the price relationship between two assets, typically one base currency and one quote currency, symbolized as <b>BASE/QUOTE</b>. For example, if you see the trading pair <strong>BTC/USDT</strong>, it means you are buying or selling <strong>Bitcoin (BTC)</strong> using <b>Tether (USDT)</b>.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p class=\"pl-5\">\n      In (<b>ETH/BTC</b>) :\n      <ol  class=\"pl-5\">\n          <li><strong>ETH</strong> is the <strong>base currency</strong>, i.e. the one you want to buy or sell.</li>\n          <li><strong>BTC</strong> is the <strong>quote currency</strong>, i.e. the one you use to pay or receive.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <span class=\"pl-5\">\n        If <b>ETH/BTC</b> = 0.07, it means that 1 <b>ETH</b> = <b>0.07 BTC</b>, so you need 0.07 <b>BTC</b> to buy 1 <b>ETH</b>, and if you sell 1 <b>ETH</b>, you will receive 0.07 <b>BTC</b>.\n      </span>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n\n    \n          <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> IMPORTANCE OF PAIR KNOWLEDGE  </b> </h2>\n     <p>\n      <br>\n     <ol class=\"list-decimal indent-2 pl-2 space-y-1 list-inside\">\n        <li><strong>They determine what you can trade</strong>\n            <p>Exchanges do not let you trade any coin for any other coin directly. You can only trade coins that have a <strong>direct pair</strong> listed.</p>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>They affect your route</strong>\n            <p>Say you have USDT and you want to buy a small token like <b> $XYZ </b>, but the exchange lists <b>$XYZ/BNB</b>. You will need to first buy <b>BNB</b> with <b>USDT</b>, then buy <b>$XYZ</b> with <b>BNB</b>.\n                <br>\n                This process is called a <strong>trading path</strong>.</p>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>They define the price you see</strong>\n            <p>You will see coin prices based on the quote currency.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li> <b> BTC/USDT</b> = $29,000; This means 1 <b>BTC</b> costs 29,000 <b>USDT</b>.</li>\n                <li><b>ETH/BTC</b> = 0.07; This means 1 <b>ETH</b> costs 0.07 <b>BTC</b>.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n    </ol>\n    </p>\n   </div>\n          <br><br>\n\n    <p><strong>NOTE : </strong> Many stablecoins (like USDT or BUSD) are <strong>quote currencies</strong> because they offer a price tied to fiat currencies such as the dollar.</p>\n\n    <br>\n    <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold\">Types of trading pairs</h2>\n    <ol class=\"\'space-y-3 list-inside pl-3\">\n        <li><strong>Crypto-to-Stablecoin</strong> (e.g., BTC/USDT) <br>\n            <span class=\"pl-5\">Good for beginners and everyday crypto transactions, with a value that is easier to understand in dollar terms.</li>\n\n        <li><strong>Crypto-to-Crypto</strong> (e.g., ETH/BTC)\n            <br> <span class=\"pl-5\"> Mainly used by experienced traders when exploring the DeFi ecosystem. </span></li>\n    </ol>\n    </section>\n\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2 class=\"text-2xl\"> Types and strategies of Crypto trading</h2>\n      <p>There are different styles and methods in crypto trading. Every trader can choose a style depending on their goals, time commitment, and risk appetite.</p>\n      <p>\n        Let\'s explore some of the most common types of crypto trading:\n      </p>\n\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">a. Spot trading</h3>\n      <p>Spot trading is like buying candy at a store: you give your money and get the candy right away. In the same way, with spot trading, you use your money (like dollars or a digital coin) to buy a cryptocurrency, such as Bitcoin, at the current market price. You receive the crypto immediately, and it becomes yours. If its price goes up later, you can sell it and make more money. But if the price goes down, you may lose some money. So, spot trading means buying and selling crypto at the current market price, just like shopping with real money. It is the most common and straightforward type of trading.</p>\n      <br>\n      \n\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">b. Margin trading</h3>\n\n      <p>\n        Margin trading is a type of trading that involves increasing your position using borrowed funds from the exchange, which allows you to trade with more money than you actually have. This can amplify your potential profits, but it also increases your risk of losses.\n\n        This type of trading will be discussed in more detail in the margin trading section of this lesson.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n\n\n\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">c. Futures trading</h3>\n      \n      <p>\n        Futures trading involves contracts to buy or sell a cryptocurrency at a future date at a predetermined price. It is often used by traders to speculate on price movements or to hedge against potential losses in their existing positions. It is a more advanced trading strategy that requires a good understanding of the market and risk management.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n\n      <h3 class=\"txt-lg font-semibold\">d. Derivatives and Options</h3>\n      <p>\n        Derivatives and options are financial instruments that derive their value from an underlying asset, such as a cryptocurrency. They allow traders to speculate on the future price movements of the asset without actually owning it. This can be a complex and risky trading strategy that requires a good understanding of the market and risk management. \n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">e. Arbitrage trading</h3>\n      <p>\n        Arbitrage trading is a strategy that involves taking advantage of price differences between different exchanges or markets. Traders buy a cryptocurrency at a lower price on one exchange and sell it at a higher price on another exchange, making a profit from the price difference. This requires quick execution and can be risky if prices change rapidly.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">f. Algorithmic trading</h3>\n      <p>\n        Algorithmic trading is a method of executing trades using computer algorithms and automated systems. It involves using predefined rules and strategies to analyze market data and execute trades at high speeds. This type of trading is often used by institutional investors and high-frequency traders to take advantage of market inefficiencies and execute large volumes of trades quickly. Due to the influx of AI and machine learning, algorithmic trading is becoming more accessible to retail traders as well.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">g. Copy trading</h3>\n      <p>\n        Copy trading is a strategy that allows traders to automatically copy the trades of experienced and successful traders. This can be done through social trading platforms or brokerage accounts that offer copy trading features. It is a way for less experienced traders to benefit from the expertise of others without having to make their own trading decisions.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold\">h. Swing trading</h3>\n      <p>\n        Swing trading is a strategy that involves holding positions for a few days to several weeks to take advantage of short-term price movements. Traders analyze charts and market trends to identify potential entry and exit points, aiming to capture smaller price swings within a larger trend. This type of trading requires patience and a good understanding of technical analysis.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n  </section>\n<br>\n\n\n');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`material`) VALUES
('  \n  <section>\n    \n        <p>\n            Crypto trading tools include all the applications a trader uses to find tokens, perform analysis, and finally execute a trade. These applications include exchanges, DEX scanning tools, market movement analyzers, block explorers, AI systems, automated bots, and more.\n            <br>\n            <br>\n            In this lesson, we will discuss popular tools and the fundamental ways to use them. However, developing dependable skill in using them takes time and conscious effort.\n\n        </p>\n\n    </section>\n<br><br>\n\n<style>\n  table {\n    border-collapse: collapse;\n    width: 100%;\n  }\n\n  th, td {\n    border: 1px solid #ccc; /* adds both vertical and horizontal lines */\n    padding: 10px;\n    text-align: left;\n  }\n  th\n  {\n    text-align: center;\n  }\n    th:last-child, td:last-child {\n        border-right: none; /* remove right border on last column */\n    }\n     th:first-child, td:first-child {\n    border-left: none; /* remove left border on last column */\n  }\n</style>\n    <section>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\"> Exchanges   </h2>\n        <br>\n\n   <table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border: collapse\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"border-bottom: solid 1px pink;\">\n      <th>Exchange</th>\n      <th>Strengths</th>\n      <th>Weaknesses</th>\n      <th>Restrictions</th>\n      <th>Terms</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Binance</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Largest trading volume globally.<br>\n        Wide selection of cryptocurrencies.<br>\n        Low trading fees.<br>\n        Advanced trading features (futures, margin, etc.).\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Complex interface for beginners.<br>\n        Regulatory scrutiny in multiple countries.<br>\n        Limited fiat support in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Restricted in the US (Binance US is a separate entity).<br>\n        KYC is required for most services.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Tiered fee structure based on volume and BNB usage.<br>\n        Margin trading with up to 10x leverage.<br>\n        Supports staking and savings products.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Coinbase</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Extremely beginner-friendly.<br>\n        High liquidity.<br>\n        Regulated in the US.<br>\n        Strong security features.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Higher fees compared to competitors.<br>\n        Fewer listed assets than Binance.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Only available in select countries.<br>\n        Full KYC and ID verification is required.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No margin trading on the basic platform.<br>\n        Pro platform available for advanced traders.<br>\n        Transparent fee schedule.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Kraken</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Regulated and secure.<br>\n        Advanced trading tools.<br>\n        Supports margin and futures.<br>\n        Low fees for high-volume traders.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Interface can be intimidating for new users.<br>\n        Limited coin selection compared to Binance.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Some features are restricted in certain US states.<br>\n        KYC is mandatory for most actions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers staking and futures.<br>\n        Up to 5x leverage on margin.<br>\n        Transparent API support.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>KuCoin</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Broad selection of altcoins.<br>\n        Low trading fees.<br>\n        User-friendly interface.<br>\n        Passive income through lending and staking.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No fiat-to-crypto trading (via third-party services only).<br>\n        History of a security breach (now improved).\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No KYC required for low-volume users.<br>\n        Limited access to fiat services in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers spot, margin, and futures trading.<br>\n        Lending features available.<br>\n        Rewards for KCS token holders.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>OKX</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Advanced trading features.<br>\n        Deep liquidity.<br>\n        Supports DeFi, Web3, and DEX connections.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Can be complex for beginners.<br>\n        Limited fiat gateways.<br>\n        Less well-known in the US.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Restricted or limited in the US.<br>\n        KYC is required for higher withdrawals and leverage.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers perpetual futures, options, and staking.<br>\n        Up to 125x leverage on derivatives.<br>\n        Built-in Web3 wallet features.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Gate.io</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Huge variety of tokens.<br>\n        Low fees.<br>\n        User-friendly interface.<br>\n        Strong security measures. <br>\n        Margin and futures support.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less well-known in the US.<br>\n        Some features can be overwhelming for beginners.<br>\n        Regulatory issues in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        KYC is required for most features.<br>\n        Restricted in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers copy trading and dual investments.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Bybit</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Fast-growing exchange.<br>\n        Strong futures platform.<br>\n        Clean UI.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less variety of altcoins compared to Binance.<br>\n        Limited fiat on-ramps.<br>\n        Not available in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        US users are restricted.<br>\n        KYC is required for high withdrawals.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Up to 100x leverage.<br>\n        Copy trading, launchpad, bots.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>MEXC</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Fast listings of new tokens.<br>\n        No KYC for small withdrawals.<br>\n        Wide asset support.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less well-known in the US.<br>\n        Limited fiat options.<br>\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Some regions are restricted.<br>\n        Limited fiat options.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Margin and futures trading.<br>\n        Launchpad, staking, earn features.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n    </section>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2>Why the restrictions?</h2>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n        There are several reasons why some exchanges place restrictions on their services, especially in certain countries or regions. These restrictions can include limitations on trading, deposits, withdrawals, or even access to the platform altogether. Here are some common reasons for these restrictions:\n      </p>\n      <ol class=\"pl-3 list-disc space-y-2 list-inside\">\n        <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Exchanges must comply with local laws and regulations, which can vary significantly between countries. Some jurisdictions have strict rules regarding cryptocurrency trading, requiring exchanges to obtain licenses or adhere to specific operational standards.</li>\n        <li><strong>Security Concerns:</strong> To protect users from potential fraud or hacking, exchanges may restrict access from regions known for high levels of cybercrime or where they cannot guarantee adequate security measures.</li>\n        <li><strong>Legal Issues:</strong> Some countries have outright bans on cryptocurrency trading or on specific types of transactions, leading exchanges to restrict access in those regions.</li>\n        <li><strong>Risk Management:</strong> Exchanges may limit services in certain areas to manage risks associated with market volatility, liquidity issues, or potential money laundering activities.</li>\n        <li><strong>Operational Challenges:</strong> Technical limitations or challenges in providing reliable services in certain regions can also lead to restrictions.</li>\n        <li><strong>Tax Compliance:</strong> Some exchanges may restrict services in countries where they cannot effectively manage tax reporting requirements for users.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n        It is important for users to be aware of these restrictions and to check the terms and conditions of the exchange they are using. If you are in a restricted region, you may need to use a different exchange that operates legally in your area or consider using decentralized exchanges (DEXs), which do not usually have such restrictions.\n      </p>\n    </section>\n    <br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2>DEX scanning tools</h2>\n      <p>\n          DEX scanning tools are essential for traders who want to analyze decentralized exchanges (DEXs) and make informed decisions. They provide real-time data on token prices, trading volumes, liquidity, and other important metrics. They help users identify potential trading opportunities, track market trends, and avoid scams or low-quality tokens.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular DEX scanning tools and their features:\n        </p>\n        <p>\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.dextools.io\" target=\"_blank\">DEXTools</a>:</strong> Offers live charts, liquidity tracking, and scam detection across DEXs like Uniswap and PancakeSwap.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://dexscreener.com\" target=\"_blank\">DexScreener</a>:</strong> Tracks live prices, volumes, and trades across chains. Great for spotting early market trends.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://tokensniffer.com\" target=\"_blank\">TokenSniffer</a>:</strong> Analyzes smart contracts to detect scams and honeypots. Useful for evaluating unknown tokens.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2>Market Movement Analyzers</h2>\n        <p>\n          Market movement analyzers are tools that help traders track and analyze the price movements of cryptocurrencies. They provide insights into market trends, trading volumes, and price patterns, enabling users to make informed trading decisions.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular market movement analyzers:\n        </p>\n        <p>\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com\" target=\"_blank\">CoinMarketCap</a>:</strong> Tracks price, volume, market cap, and trends. Useful for gauging overall market sentiment.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://cryptoquant.com\" target=\"_blank\">CryptoQuant</a>:</strong> Provides insights using exchange flows, whale tracking, and miner activity for market predictions.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://santiment.net\" target=\"_blank\">Santiment</a>:</strong> Combines social media, developer, and on-chain data to offer predictive signals.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n      </p>\n      <br><br>\n\n        <h2>Block explorers</h2>\n        <p>\n          Block explorers are essential tools for anyone involved in cryptocurrency trading or blockchain technology. They allow users to view and analyze transactions, blocks, and addresses on a blockchain network. These tools provide transparency and help users verify transactions, track wallet balances, and monitor network activity.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular block explorers for different blockchain networks:\n        </p>\n        \n        <p>\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://etherscan.io\" target=\"_blank\">Etherscan (Ethereum)</a>:</strong> Explore Ethereum transactions, wallet balances, and smart contract activities.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://bscscan.com\" target=\"_blank\">BscScan (Binance Smart Chain)</a>:</strong> Offers similar functionality for BSC, including DeFi interaction tracking.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://solscan.io\" target=\"_blank\">Solscan (Solana)</a>:</strong> Used for exploring Solana blockchain activity, including transactions and validator data.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2>AI systems</h2>\n        <p>\n          AI systems are increasingly being integrated into crypto trading to provide advanced analytics, predictive modeling, and automated trading strategies. These systems can analyze vast amounts of data, identify patterns, and make real-time decisions to optimize trading outcomes.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular AI systems used in crypto trading:\n        </p>\n        <p>\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://app.intotheblock.com\" target=\"_blank\">IntoTheBlock</a>:</strong> AI-based insights like whale concentration, holder behavior, and market intelligence.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.kaiko.com\" target=\"_blank\">Kaiko AI</a>:</strong> Institutional-grade AI analytics focusing on liquidity, market data, and trade analysis.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://openai.com/chatgpt\" target=\"_blank\">ChatGPT (Custom)</a>:</strong> When integrated with data feeds, it can assist with predictions, strategy creation, and sentiment analysis.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2>Automated bots</h2>\n        <p>\n          Automated trading bots are software programs that execute trades on behalf of users based on predefined strategies or algorithms. They can help traders take advantage of market opportunities 24/7 without the need for constant monitoring. Here are some popular automated trading bots:\n        </p>\n        <p>\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://3commas.io\" target=\"_blank\">3Commas</a>:</strong> Multi-strategy bot platform supporting DCA, grid, and copy trading on major exchanges.\n          </li> \n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.pionex.com\" target=\"_blank\">Pionex</a>:</strong> Comes with built-in grid and arbitrage bots. Beginner-friendly and reliable for passive income.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://hummingbot.org\" target=\"_blank\">Hummingbot</a>:</strong> Open-source, code-driven bot suitable for advanced users focused on liquidity mining and custom strategies.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n    </section>\n    <br><br>\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> PLATFORM UTILITY TIP </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      As a beginner, most of these tools may not make sense to you yet, but as you progress in your crypto journey, you will find them useful. It is important to take your time to learn and understand how each tool works and how it can enhance your trading experience.\n      <br>\n       This list, though not exhaustive, helps answer the questions of \"what to buy, when to buy, why to buy, and how to buy\" in the crypto ecosystem. There are more tools and alternatives than the ones listed here, and you will discover them as you continue to explore the crypto space. They are essential for making informed trading decisions and maximizing your potential profits. \n       <br>\n       This lesson is only an introduction to these tools. You will learn more about them through experimentation, experience, and future lessons focused on them.\n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br>\n'),
('<section>\n  \n        <p>\n            Funding your wallet simply means adding real crypto to your wallet. Crypto assets can be obtained from exchanges using fiat (ordinary money), or they can be received from someone who already has them and decides to send some to you.\n            <br>\n\n            <br>\n            In this lesson, we will briefly discuss this basic process.\n\n        </p>\n        <p>  \n           Receiving crypto from another person is a basic process. Whether on a centralized exchange or a wallet, all you have to do is copy your wallet address on the correct network and send it to them.\n          <br> If you are both on the same centralized crypto exchange, you may be able to send them your user ID or even your username, depending on what the exchange allows. \n          </p>\n          <br>\n\n   <h2>Here\'s a guide on copying and sharing your wallet address </h2>\n   <br>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside indent-4 pl-3 \">\n      <li>Open your wallet and tap \"Receive\" to display your address or QR code.</li>\n      <li>Take note of the network for the token you want to receive. Crypto sent through the wrong network may not be recoverable.</li>\n      <li>Digitally copy the address on that network. <b>DO NOT TYPE WALLET ADDRESSES</b> or write them down manually, because you are very likely to make mistakes.</li>     \n     <li>Ask the sender to include the correct memo or tag if required.</li>\n      <li>After the sender sends the crypto, monitor the transaction with the provided transaction hash on a blockchain explorer.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n  <div>\n    <h2>\n      Buying from an exchange\n    </h2>\n    <br>\n            \n        <h2>    1. Bank transfer (via exchange or on-ramp) </h2>\n       <p> Bank transfers are one of the most common ways to convert local currency into cryptocurrency. Many centralized exchanges and fiat on-ramps accept bank deposits, ACH (US), SEPA (EU), or local bank transfers.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n       <b> Steps</b>\n       <br>\n        <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside  indent-4 pl-3\">\n          <li>Create an account on a trusted exchange or payment provider and complete KYC if required.</li>\n          <li>Locate the deposit page for your selected currency.</li>\n          <li>Follow the deposit instructions, noting details like account number, reference code, and any required tags.</li>\n          <li>Make the deposit as instructed.</li>\n          <li>After your payment is verified, your asset will be deposited into your exchange wallet. Withdraw it to your external wallet if necessary.</li>  \n      </ol>\n<br><br>\n\n\n      <h2>2. With credit/debit cards</h2>\n\n      <p>\n         Cards are fast and user-friendly, but they often carry higher fees and lower limits compared to bank transfers.\n        To buy from an exchange using a debit or credit card, some exchanges require a verification process that involves submitting your personal documents.\n        <br>\n          After this process is completed, you can purchase any cryptocurrency of your choice using fiat, or by first buying USDT and then using the purchased USDT to buy your coin of choice.\n        <br>\n          \n          The steps for this are usually simple and self-explanatory on any exchange.\n          \n      </p> \n     <b> Steps</b> \n      <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside indent-4 pl-3\">\n      <li>Choose a provider or exchange that supports card purchases.</li>\n      <li>Locate the deposit section and choose debit/credit cards.</li>\n      <li>Enter your card details and the amount of fiat to convert.</li>\n      <li>Confirm the purchase. The crypto usually arrives instantly in the exchange account or in-app wallet.</li>\n      </ol>\n\n<br>\n<br>\n   <h2>3. Buying USDT using P2P</h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n    If the exchange you are using does not support direct fiat conversions due to government restrictions, regulatory laws, or high transaction fees, you can buy USDT using Peer-to-Peer (P2P) transactions. P2P platforms on centralized exchanges match buyers and sellers directly, which is especially useful in places where regulated on-ramps are limited. You can pay another person via bank transfer, mobile money, or cash and receive crypto through escrow on the P2P platform. This works by placing an order with a merchant, making payment directly to the merchant\'s account, and then receiving your USDT after the merchant verifies the payment. In this setup, the exchange serves as an escrow between you and the merchant by holding the merchant\'s crypto and releasing it to you after you have paid and the merchant has confirmed your payment. If any issues arise during the process, the exchange is expected to resolve the dispute and punish defaulters.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <b>Steps</b>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside pl-3\">\n      <li>Create and verify your P2P account.</li>\n      <li>Find a reputable seller with good completion rates and sensible pricing.</li>\n      <li>Start a trade, follow the platform\'s escrow instructions, and complete the off-platform payment.</li>\n      <li>Confirm the release of the crypto once payment is verified.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n    <br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> NOTE </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n       <b>1.</b>\n    <span>USDT is the most widely used and most popular quote currency on exchanges because it is a stablecoin with a value equal to the US dollar. It can easily be converted into almost any other asset of your choice.</span>\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    \n    <span>\n    <b>2.</b>  Do not perform P2P negotiations or transactions outside the exchange. This is a common method scammers use to defraud unsuspecting users. Because the exchange will have no evidence of your transaction, the scammer may escape punishment and your funds may be lost.  </span>\n    <br>\n    <br>\n    <span>\n          <b>3</b>\n          <br>\n          Different funding methods come with different fees and transaction charges, so always monitor the fees and charges to avoid using your funds inefficiently.\n    </span>\n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br>\n\n<div class=\'overflow-x-auto\'>\n  <h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">A quick comparison between the exchange methods</h2>\n      <table class=\'min-w-full border border-gray-300 text-sm\'>\n                <thead>\n                              <tr>\n                                                <th class=\'border px-3 py-2 text-left\'>Method</th>                <th class=\'border px-3 py-2 text-left\'>Pros</th>                <th class=\'border px-3 py-2 text-left\'>Cons</th>            \n                                              </tr>        \n                                            </thead>       \n                                              \n                                              \n                                              <tbody>\n                                                              <tr>\n                                                                                <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'><b>Bank Transfer</b></td>                <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>Low fees, direct from bank, usually with higher limits.</td>                <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>Slower processing, and bank restrictions are possible.</td>           \n                                                               </tr>           \n                                                                                \n <tr>                \n       <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'><b>Credit Card</b></td>\n                                                                                                                          <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>Fast, convenient, and instant purchase.</td>                \n                                                                                                                  <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>High fees, risk of debt, and some banks block crypto transactions due to regulations.</td>            \n                                                                                                                \n</tr>            \n                                                                                                                  <tr>\n                                                                                                                            <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'> <b> P2P </b></td>                \n                                                                                                                            <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>More payment options, and often better rates.</td>\n                                                                                                                          <td class=\'border px-3 py-2\'>Risk of scams, requires caution, and may involve slower dispute resolution.</td>\n                                                                                                                    </tr>        \n                                                                                                                                  </tbody>    \n                                                                                                                                </table>\n                                                                                                                              \n          </div>\n  </div>\n\n </section>\n'),
(' <section>\n     \n        <p>\n         The aim of every investment is to make profit, and this also applies to crypto investments. The earlier parts of these lessons focused on the \"what is\" and \"how to\" of crypto. This particular lesson is meant to expose you to the rationale behind crypto investing.\n         <br>\n         <br>\n         \n         One common mistake many crypto newcomers make is believing that crypto is a get-rich-quick scheme, where you walk in today with little or nothing and walk out tomorrow as a billionaire. The harsh truth is that crypto is far more complex and volatile than that. Although the opportunities and possibilities are broad, you will still need patience, knowledge, and strategy. \n         <br>\n         <br>\n         \n         Money is not manufactured in crypto; instead, money flows, and your responsibility as an investor is to position yourself so that the money flows to you. There are thousands of crypto tokens and projects, with many more still being developed as you read this, so the task of finding the right project to invest in is one of the hardest parts of this industry, even before deciding when to buy and when to sell.\n         <br>\n         <br>\n\n         The best time to invest in any project is often in its early stages, but how do you know whether a project is not just another baseless hype, or whether it will stagnate your capital and leave it unproductive far longer than you planned? This is why knowledge and experience can only be built over time. There is no shortcut.\n         <br>\n         <br>        \n        </p> \n        \n        <h2>Investment strategy based on timeframe</h2>\n         <p>\n        There are different crypto investing and trading strategies. Here, they are grouped according to the expected timeframe for returns.\n        </p>\n        <br>\n       <ol class=\"space-y-2 list-inside \">\n\n       <li><b> 1. Scalping (Very Short-Term: Minutes to Hours) </b>\n\n        Making dozens of quick trades daily to take advantage of tiny price movements. The goal is to capture small profits repeatedly within very short time frames.\n</li>\n\n\n        <li><b>2. Day Trading (Short-Term: Within a Day)</b>\n        Buying and selling crypto within the same day to profit from intraday volatility. Positions are closed before the day ends to avoid overnight risks.\n       </li>\n\n\n        \n       <li><b> 3. Swing Trading (Medium-Term: Days to Weeks)</b>\n\n        Holding positions for a few days to several weeks to ride market swings and capture medium-sized gains.</li>\n\n       <li><b>4. Position Trading / Holding (Long-Term: Months to Years)</b>\n\n        Buying strong coins and holding them through market ups and downs with the expectation of major appreciation over time. In crypto, this is commonly called HODLing.\n</li>\n        \n      <li>\n       <b>5. Staking & Yield Farming (Passive Long-Term: Continuous Income)</b>\n        Locking coins in a network (staking) or providing liquidity (yield farming) to earn rewards, generating passive income while waiting for long-term price growth.\n       </li>\n\n       </ol>\n\n        <br>  \n        <br>\n         <h2>Investment strategy based on trade type</h2>\n             <p>\n               Crypto profits are largely about timed entries and exits. There are different methods, regardless of time strategy, that traders use to enter and exit the market in a bid to make profits. These methods include:\n\n               <ol class=\"space-y-2 list-inside \">\n\n                                \n                         <li>\n                                     <b>1. Spot Trading</b>\n                                     Buying and selling cryptocurrencies directly at current market prices.\n\n                                       Profits come from price appreciation or short-term fluctuations.\n\n                           </li>\n\n\n                         <li>  <b>2. Margin Trading</b>\n\n                         Trading with borrowed funds to increase position size.\n\n                         This amplifies both profits and losses through leverage.\n                       </li>\n\n                       <li>\n                         <b>          3. Futures trading </b>   \n                         Contracts to buy or sell crypto at a predetermined price in the future.\n\n                         Traders can speculate on both rising (long) and falling (short) markets.\n\n                       </li>\n\n                       <li>\n                         <b> 4. Arbitrage Trading </b>\n                         Exploiting price differences of the same crypto across different exchanges.\n\n                         It involves fast execution and is often automated.\n\n                       </li>\n                       </ol>\n\n                       <br><br>\n\n            \n\n             </p>\n\n             <div class=\"quickbox\">\n        <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> PRICE PREDICTION </b> </h2>\n       <br>\n        </p>  The future price movement of an asset can be tentatively predicted, and this prediction forms the basis for combining time-based and trade-type strategies. For example, an investor predicts that the price of BTC will increase within 24 hours, so they decide to enter a BTC futures trade using high leverage. After 24 hours, they either recover profits if the prediction is correct or take losses if the trade moves against them.\n               So, time-based and trade-type strategies are not mutually exclusive; rather, they often work hand in hand.\n             <p>\n      </div>\n             <br><br>\n\n\n\n\n\n             <h2>Investment economics</h2>\n             <p>\n               Crypto assets follow the same laws of supply and demand when it comes to price. How much of an asset is available in the open market, who is interested in it, what real use the asset has, whether it is marketed well enough, and who created it are all important questions. These questions, and many more, help answer what to buy and what not to buy, and they serve as a guide toward predicting the future of any asset.\n\n               <br>\n               <br>\n               You may ask, \"How do I know what to buy, when to buy, and when to sell?\" The direct answer is that nobody knows for sure what will happen next. However, anyone can make an informed speculation, and because speculation remains speculation, the statement \"Invest what you can afford to lose\" became popular. This is because the market can move in any direction, which can mean profits in one direction and liquidation in the other.\n               <br>\n               <br>\n               Spot holders have a common saying: \"You don\'t lose until you sell.\" This is meant to encourage holders who are at a loss not to sell, because there is a belief that the token\'s price will rise again and position them for profit. This is not entirely true when you consider the time value of the money locked in and the fact that nobody knows exactly when such an asset will recover and rise in price. However, your knowledge and strategy may still lead you to decide that holding a dipping token is the right choice.\n               \n\n              </p>\n\n\n\n</section>\n');

